{"title_page": "Wet market", "text_new": "{{Short description|Market selling perishable goods, generally including produce, meat, or food animals}}\n{{Chinese|pic=WetmarketHK.jpg|picsize=250px|c=[[wiktionary:\u8857\u5e02|\u8857\u5e02]]|j=gaai<sup>1</sup> si<sup>5</sup>|l=street market|showflag=j|ci={{IPAc-yue|g|aai|1|.|s|i|5}}}}\n<!-- \"\u8857\u5e02\" only means \"wet market\" in Cantonese, so pinyin here is unnecessary -->\n\nA '''wet market''' (also called a '''public market''')<ref name=\"ZSCSH\">{{Cite journal|last=Zhong|first=Taiyang|last2=Si|first2=Zhenzhong|last3=Crush|first3=Jonathan|last4=Scott|first4=Steffanie|last5=Huang|first5=Xianjin|year=2019|title=Achieving urban food security through a hybrid public-private food provisioning system: the case of Nanjing, China|journal=Food Security|language=en|volume=11|issue=5|pages=1071\u20131086|doi=10.1007/s12571-019-00961-8|issn=1876-4517}}</ref><ref name=\"Morales-2009\">{{Cite journal|last=Morales|first=Alfonso|year=2009|title=Public Markets as Community Development Tools|journal=Journal of Planning Education and Research|language=en|volume=28|issue=4|pages=426\u2013440|doi=10.1177/0739456X08329471|issn=0739-456X}}</ref><ref name=\"Morales-2011\">{{Cite journal|last=Morales|first=Alfonso|year=2011|title=Marketplaces: Prospects for Social, Economic, and Political Development|journal=Journal of Planning Literature|language=en|volume=26|issue=1|pages=3\u201317|doi=10.1177/0885412210388040|issn=0885-4122}}</ref> is a [[marketplace]] selling fresh meat, fish, [[greengrocer|produce]], and other perishable goods as distinguished from \"dry markets\" that sell durable goods such as fabric and electronics.<ref>Wholesale Markets: Planning and Design Manual (Fao Agricultural Services Bulletin) (No 90)</ref><ref name=\"OED\">{{cite web |url=https://www.oed.com/view/Entry/227970 |title=wet, adj. |publisher=[[Oxford English Dictionary]] |quote=wet market  n. South-East Asian a market for the sale of fresh meat, fish, and produce  |accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"brown\">{{Cite journal|last=Brown|first=Allison|year=2001|title=Counting Farmers Markets|journal=Geographical Review|volume=91|issue=4|pages=655\u2013674|doi=10.2307/3594724|jstor=3594724}}</ref> The term wet market is often used to signify a '''live animal market''' that slaughters animals upon customer purchase.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Woo|first=Patrick CY|last2=Lau|first2=Susanna KP|last3=Yuen|first3=Kwok-yung|year=2006|title=Infectious diseases emerging from Chinese wet-markets: zoonotic origins of severe respiratory viral infections|journal=Current Opinion in Infectious Diseases|language=en|volume=19|issue=5|pages=401\u2013407|doi=10.1097/01.qco.0000244043.08264.fc|pmid=16940861|issn=0951-7375}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Wan|first=X.F.|year=2012|title=Lessons from Emergence of A/Goose/Guangdong/1996-Like H5N1 Highly Pathogenic Avian Influenza Viruses and Recent Influenza Surveillance Efforts in Southern China: Lessons from Gs/Gd/96-like H5N1 HPAIVs|journal=Zoonoses and Public Health|language=en|volume=59|pages=32\u201342|doi=10.1111/j.1863-2378.2012.01497.x|pmc=4119829|pmid=22958248}}</ref> Wet markets are common throughout the world.<ref name=\"nw\">{{cite news |url=https://www.newsweek.com/peta-launches-petition-close-wet-markets-coronavirus-1494803 |publisher=[[Newsweek]] |title= PETA LAUNCHES PETITION TO SHUT DOWN LIVE ANIMAL MARKETS THAT BREED DISEASES LIKE COVID-19 |first=Khaleda |last=Rahman |date=28 March 2020 |accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Reardon|first=Thomas|last2=Timmer|first2=C. Peter|last3=Minten|first3=Bart|date=2012-07-31|title=Supermarket revolution in Asia and emerging development strategies to include small farmers|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America|volume=109|issue=31|pages=12332\u201312337|doi=10.1073/pnas.1003160108|issn=0027-8424|pmc=3412023|pmid=21135250|bibcode=2012PNAS..10912332R}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2020/01/29/800725826/why-wet-markets-are-the-perfect-place-to-spread-disease|title=Why Wet Markets Are The Perfect Place To Spread Disease|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> Wet markets include a wide variety of markets, such as [[farmers' market]]s, [[fish market]]s, and [[Wildlife trade|wildlife market]]s.<ref name=\"ZSCSH\"/><ref name=\"lynteris-fearnley\"/> \n\nWet markets containing live animals, especially those which combine domesticated and wild animals, but also those which carry wildlife products have been linked to outbreaks of [[zoonotic disease]]s including [[coronavirus disease 2019]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"ZSCSH\"/><ref name=\":2\" /> Not all wet markets carry living animals or wildlife.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"ZSCSH\" /><ref name=\"lynteris-fearnley\"/> Wet markets were banned from holding wildlife in China in 2003, after the [[2002\u20132004 SARS outbreak]], which was directly tied to such practices.<ref name=\":2\" /> Such regulations were lifted before being put into place again in 2020,<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/74f1b26e-53c0-11ea-90ad-25e377c0ee1f|title=Coronavirus piles pressure on China's exotic animal trade|last=Yu|first=Sun|last2=Liu|first2=Xinning|date=2020-02-23|website=Financial Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> with other countries proposing similar bans.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/eba067c4-69ce-11ea-800d-da70cff6e4d3|title=The economic case for ending wildlife trade hits home in Vietnam|last=Reed|first=John|date=2020-03-19|website=Financial Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\nMedia reports that fail to distinguish between all wet markets from those with live produce or wildlife have been blamed for fueling [[List of incidents of xenophobia and racism related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|xenophobia related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=\"FP\">{{cite news |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/01/27/coronavirus-covid19-dont-blame-bat-soup-for-the-virus/ |publisher=[[Foreign Policy]] |title=Don't Blame Bat Soup for the Coronavirus |last=Palmer |first=James |date=27 January 2020 |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"lynteris-fearnley\"/>\n\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n==Terminology==\nAs early as 1948, \"wet market\" was identified as a name in English for a type of market.<ref name=\"IRCD\">{{cite web|url=https://northeastiowarcd.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/IA-FM-Chapter-1.pdf|title=Chapter 1: What is a Farmer's Market?|publisher=Northeast Iowa Resource Conservation & Development|accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref> The term \"wet market\" originated from [[Hong Kong English]] and entered the ''[[Oxford English Dictionary]]'' in 2016.<ref name=\":5\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/may/13/east-asian-words-oxford-english-dictionary-hong-kong-singapore-oed|title=East Asian words make it into ''Oxford English Dictionary''|date=13 May 2016|work=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=22 May 2018|agency=[[Agence France-Presse]]|location=London}}</ref>\n\nThe \"wet\" in \"wet market\" refers to the constantly wet floors as a consequence of the spraying of fresh produce and cleaning of meat and seafood stalls.<ref>{{cite book|last=Burton|first=Dawn|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hiFxfmZteFgC|title=Cross-Cultural Marketing: Theory, Practice and Relevance|publisher=[[Routledge]]|year=2008|isbn=9781134060177|page=146}}</ref><ref name=\"Reuters\" /> Sometimes, the term wet market is used to signify a live animal market that sells directly to consumers.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\" />\n\n===Synonyms===\nThe term \"public market\" is synonymous with \"wet market\",<ref name=\"ZSCSH\"/><ref name=\"Morales-2009\"/><ref name=\"Morales-2011\"/> although it may sometimes refer exclusively to state-owned and community-owned wet markets.<ref name=\"ZSCSH\"/><ref name=\"Morales-2009\"/><ref name=\"Morales-2011\"/>\n\nWet markets may also be called \"fresh food markets\" and \"good food markets\" when referring to markets consisting of numerous competing vendors primarily selling fruits and vegetables.<ref name=\"brown\" />\n\n==Around the world==\nThe term \"wet market\", which specifies markets that sell fresh produce and meat, includes a broad variety of markets.<ref name=\"ZSCSH\" /><ref name=\"lynteris-fearnley\" /> Wet markets can be categorized according to their ownership structure ([[Privately held company|privately owned]], [[State-owned enterprise|state-owned]], or [[Community ownership|community-owned]]), scale ([[Wholesaling|wholesale]] or [[retail]]), and produce (vegetables, slaughtered meat, live animals).<ref name=\"ZSCSH\" /><ref name=\"lynteris-fearnley\" /> They can be further subcategorized based on whether the meat sold comes from [[Domestication of animals|domesticated]] or [[wildlife|wild animal]]s.<ref name=\"ZSCSH\" /><ref name=\"lynteris-fearnley\" />\n\n=== China ===\n[[File:Seafood section of Sanqi Baihui Market, Hall 1 (20190519152946).jpg|thumb|Seafood section of Sanqi Baihui Market in [[Beijing]], [[China]]]]\nAs of 2018, wet markets remain the most prevalent food outlet in urban regions of China despite the rise of supermarket chains since the 1990s.<ref name=\"sustainability-2018\">{{Cite journal |last=Zhong |first=Taiyang |last2=Si |first2=Zhenzhong |last3=Crush |first3=Jonathan |last4=Xu |first4=Zhiying |last5=Huang |first5=Xianjin |last6=Scott |first6=Steffanie |last7=Tang |first7=Shuangshuang |last8=Zhang |first8=Xiang |year=2018 |title=The Impact of Proximity to Wet Markets and Supermarkets on Household Dietary Diversity in Nanjing City, China |url=http://www.mdpi.com/2071-1050/10/5/1465 |journal=Sustainability |language=en |volume=10 |issue=5 |pages=1465 |doi=10.3390/su10051465 |issn=2071-1050}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, all roadside markets in [[Hangzhou]] were banned and moved indoors.<ref name=\"SD-Hangzhou\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.shine.cn/feature/travel/1805315493/ |publisher=[[Shanghai Daily]] |title=Regeneration and reinvention of Hangzhou's wet markets |last=Jia |first=Shi |date=31 May 2018 |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> In 2003, wet markets across China were banned from holding wildlife after the 2002\u20132004 SARS outbreak, which was directly tied to such practices.<ref name=\":2\" /> In 2014, live poultry was banned from all markets in Hangzhou due to the [[Influenza A virus subtype H7N9#Reported cases in 2013|H7N9 avian influenza outbreak]].<ref name=\"SD-Hangzhou\"/>\n\nDuring the 2010s, \"smart markets\" equipped with e-payment terminals emerged as traditional wet markets faced increasing competition from discount stores.<ref name=\"SD-Hangzhou\"/>\n\nThe origin of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was linked to the [[Huanan Seafood Wholesale Market]] in [[Wuhan]], [[China]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uchicagomedicine.org/forefront/prevention-and-screening-articles/wuhan-coronavirus|title=COVID-19: What we know so far about the 2019 novel coronavirus|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Following the outbreak, proposals were made to ban the operation of wet markets selling wild animals for human consumption.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=http://cbc.ca/radio/thecurrent/the-current-for-feb-17-2020-1.5466207/experts-call-for-global-ban-on-live-animal-markets-wildlife-trade-amidst-coronavirus-outbreak-1.5466219|title=Experts call for global ban on live animal markets, wildlife trade amidst coronavirus outbreak|date=February 17, 2020|work=CBC|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{citation|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2020/jan/24/calls-for-global-ban-wild-animal-markets-amid-coronavirus-outbreak|publisher=The Guardian|date=24 January 2020|title=Calls for global ban on wild animal markets amid coronavirus outbreak|author=Sarah Boseley}}</ref> A few others have pointed out that most wet markets in China do not sell wild animals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://radiichina.com/wet-markets-wild-animals-china/|title=No, You Won't Find \"Wild Animals\" in Most of China's Wet Markets|last=Bossons|first=Matthew|date=2020-02-25|website=RADII|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theconversation.com/why-shutting-down-chinese-wet-markets-could-be-a-terrible-mistake-130625|title=Why shutting down Chinese 'wet markets' could be a terrible mistake|last=Lynteris|first=Christos|last2=Fearnley|first2=Lyle|website=The Conversation|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\nThe Huanan Seafood Wholesale Market was shut down on 1 January 2020. The Chinese government subsequently announced a permanent ban on the sale of wild animal products at wet markets.<ref name=\"sierraclub.org\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sierraclub.org/sierra/china-could-end-global-trade-wildlife|title=China Could End the Global Trade in Wildlife|date=2020-03-26|website=Sierra Club|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref>{{citation|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/china-bans-wildlife-trade-consumption-coronavirus-2020-2|publisher=Business Insider|date=25 February 2020|title=China just banned the trade and consumption of wild animals. Experts think the coronavirus jumped from live animals to people at a market.|author=Aylin Woodward}}</ref> By {{date|2020-04-02|DMY}}, some temporarily closed wet markets in China were reported to have been reopened, leading to public criticism of the Chinese government's handling of wild animal trade by [[Anthony Fauci]] and [[Lindsey Graham]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=O'reilly|first=Andrew|url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/lindsey-graham-asks-china-to-close-all-operating-wet-markets-after-coronavirus-outbreak|title=Lindsey Graham asks China to close 'all operating wet markets' after coronavirus outbreak|date=2020-04-02|work=Fox News|access-date=2020-04-03|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Bowden|first=John|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/senate/490834-graham-asks-colleagues-to-support-call-for-china-to-close-wet-markets|title=Graham asks colleagues to support call for China to close wet markets|date=2020-04-02|work=The Hill|access-date=2020-04-03|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Politico\">{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/04/03/anthony-fauci-foreign-wet-markets-shutdown-162975 |title='Shut down those things right away': Calls to close 'wet markets' ramp up pressure on China |first=Quint |last=Forgey |date=3 April 2020 |work=Politico |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Hong Kong ====\n[[File:HK Bridges Street Market.JPG|thumb|The building that housed the former [[Bridges Street Market]] in [[Hong Kong]]]]\nIn 1920, the Reclamation Street Market was opened in [[Hong Kong]]. Due to structure problems, Reclamation Street Market was removed by the government in 1953.<ref>{{Cite book|title=\u7b2c\u4e8c\u5c46\u5eff\u4e00\u4e16\u7d00\u83ef\u4eba\u5730\u5340\u6b77\u53f2\u6559\u80b2\u8ad6\u6587\u96c6|trans-title=Second Collection of Historical Education Papers on Chinese in the 21st Century |author=Bao Shaolin|publisher=Zhonghua Book Company (Hong Kong) Limited.|year=2012|language=Chinese|isbn=|location=|pages=332}}</ref> In 1957, Yau Ma Tei Street Market launched to replace the Reclamation Street Market.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mmis.hkpl.gov.hk/coverpage/-/coverpage/view?p_r_p_-1078056564_c=QF757YsWv59a9PNz3lScYjii24oro5jB&_coverpage_WAR_mmisportalportlet_o=18&_coverpage_WAR_mmisportalportlet_actual_q=%28%20%28%20allTermsMandatory%3A%28true%29%20OR+all_dc.title%3A%28%E6%B2%B9%E9%BA%BB%E5%9C%B0%E8%A1%97%E5%B8%82%29%20OR+all_dc.creator%3A%28%E6%B2%B9%E9%BA%BB%E5%9C%B0%E8%A1%97%E5%B8%82%29%20OR+all_dc.contributor%3A%28%E6%B2%B9%E9%BA%BB%E5%9C%B0%E8%A1%97%E5%B8%82%29%20OR+all_dc.subject%3A%28%E6%B2%B9%E9%BA%BB%E5%9C%B0%E8%A1%97%E5%B8%82%29%20OR+fulltext%3A%28%E6%B2%B9%E9%BA%BB%E5%9C%B0%E8%A1%97%E5%B8%82%29%20OR+all_dc.description%3A%28%E6%B2%B9%E9%BA%BB%E5%9C%B0%E8%A1%97%E5%B8%82%29%20%29%20%29&_coverpage_WAR_mmisportalportlet_sort_order=desc&_coverpage_WAR_mmisportalportlet_sort_field=score&_coverpage_WAR_mmisportalportlet_log=Y|title=\u6cb9\u9ebb\u5730\u65b0\u5efa\u8857\u5e02\u6628\u6668\u958b\u5e55\u5f8c\u71df\u696d|trans-title=Yau Ma Tei New Market opened after opening yesterday morning|language=Chinese|last=|first=|date=1957-11-02|work=Hong Kong Business Daily|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref> There were fixed-pitch stalls which sold vegetables, fruits, seafood, beef, pork, and poultry. Also, there were stalls selling baby chickens, baby ducks, and three-striped box turtles as pets.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hkmemory.hk/collections/oral_history/All_Items_OH/oha_70/records/index.html|title=Yau Ma Tei's wet markets in the early post-war period|date=2011-03-29|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref>\n\nCentral Market was launched on 16 May 1842. Its position was central, on Queen's Road. In this market, people could find all kinds of meat, fruit and vegetables, poultry, salt fish, fresh fish, weighing rooms and money changers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sunzi.lib.hku.hk/hkgro/view/g1842/728468.pdf|title=The Friend Of China, and Hong Kong Gazette|date=1842-05-12|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref>\n\nIn Hong Kong, wet markets are most frequented by older residents, those with lower incomes, and domestic helpers who serve approximately 10 percent of Hong Kong's residents.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emeraldinsight.com/journals.htm?articleid=1412265&show=abstract |title=EmeraldInsight |website=EmeraldInsight.com |accessdate=2016-08-01}}</ref> Wet markets have become destinations for tourists to \"see the real Hong Kong\".<ref>{{cite news| url=http://intransit.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/03/18/a-guide-to-hong-kongs-wet-markets/ | newspaper=[[The New York Times]] | first=Sei | last=Chong | title=A Guide to Hong Kong's Wet Markets | date=18 March 2011|accessdate=2016-08-01}}</ref> Many of the wet market buildings are owned by property investment firms and as a result the price of food can vary from market to market.<ref>{{cite news|author=Elmer W. Cagape |url=http://asiancorrespondent.com/64501/expensive-food-tung-chung-hk/ |title=Tung Chung town pays the most for food in Hong Kong |work=Asian Correspondent |date=2011-09-08 |accessdate=2016-08-01}}</ref>\n\nIn 1994, wet markets accounted for 70% of produce sales and 50% of meat sales in Hong Kong.<ref name=\"ATH-7\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=urH_3knhcjAC&dq |title=Agricultural Trade Highlights |publisher=[[Foreign Agricultural Service]] |year=1994 |page=7}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008 the government of Hong Kong proposed that all poultry should be slaughtered at central abattoirs to combat the spread of [[avian flu]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.news.gov.hk/isd/ebulletin/en/category/issues/080614/html/080613en05005.htm |title=Central abattoir set for 2011 |website=Archive.news.gov.hk |date=2008-06-13 |accessdate=2016-08-01}}</ref>\n\nHong Kong's wet markets use red lampshades to make the food look fresher.<ref>{{cite news|script-title=zh:\u8d85\u5de8\u8857\u5e02\u71c8\u73fe\u8eab\u5546\u5834|trans-title=Super large wet market red lamps appears in shopping mall|url=http://www.sharpdaily.hk/article/news/20120914/134111|accessdate=19 November 2012|newspaper=Sharp Daily|date=14 September 2012|language=Chinese|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121108070308/http://www.sharpdaily.hk/article/news/20120914/134111|archive-date=8 November 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Mexico===\n[[File:Mercado 20 de noviembre - Oaxaca de Ju\u00e1rez - 10.jpg|thumb|Fresh meat section of the Mercado 20 de Noviembre in [[Oaxaca City|Oaxaca]], [[Mexico]]]]\nSome traditional [[Mexico|Mexican]] open-air markets called ''[[tianguis]]'', such as the Mercado Margarita Maza de Ju\u00e1rez in [[Oaxaca City|Oaxaca]], are separated into a wet market (''zona h\u00fameda'') and a dry market (''zona seca'').<ref name=\"imparcial\">{{cite news |url=https://imparcialoaxaca.mx/oaxaca/304648/central-de-abasto-bomba-de-tiempo-y-nido-de-delincuencia/ |title=Central de Abasto: bomba de tiempo y nido de delincuencia |publisher=[[El Imparcial (Oaxaca)]] |date=9 May 2019 |accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Singapore===\nIn the early 1990s, the slaughter of animals was banned in 12 inner-city markets and 22 wet market centers in [[Singapore]].<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RjxIAAAAYAAJ |title=U.S. Trade and Prospects: Dairy, livestock, and poultry products |year=1992 |publisher=The Service |author=United States. Foreign Agricultural Service. Dairy, Livestock, and Poultry Division, United States. World Agricultural Outlook Board |page=3}}</ref> In 2020, the [[National Environment Agency]] issued advisories for \"high standards of hygiene and cleanliness\" for the 83 markets that it oversees.<ref name=\"Reuters\">{{cite news|last=Chandran|first=Rina|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/southeast-asia-health-markets/traditional-markets-blamed-for-virus-outbreak-are-lifeline-for-asias-poor-idUSL8N2A5201|title=Traditional markets blamed for virus outbreak are lifeline for Asia's poor|date=7 February 2020|accessdate=4 April 2020|publisher=[[Reuters]]}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Tekka Centre|Tekka Market]], [[Tiong Bahru#Tiong Bahru Market|Tiong Bahru Market]], and [[Chinatown, Singapore#Geography|Chinatown Complex Market]] are prominent wet markets containing seasonal fruit, fresh vegetables, imported beef, and live seafood.<ref name=\"cnn-sg\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/travel/article/singapore-wet-market/index.html |publisher=[[CNN]] |title=Singapore wet markets: Reminder of bygone days |date=22 June 2015 |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Taiwan===\nIn 1997, a report by the [[Taipei]] city government indicated that the city had 61 major wet markets with almost 10,000 registered vendors.<ref name=\"twt\">{{cite news |url=https://taiwantoday.tw/news.php?post=12589&unit=8,29,32,45 |title=Are Wet Markets Drying Up? |publisher=[[Taiwan Today]] |last=Trappey |first=Charles V. |date=1 March 1997 |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> The report also indicated that most of the city's wet markets were in serious need of repair and that almost 3,500 of the vendor stalls lay vacant.<ref name=\"twt\"/>\n\nThe Nanmen Market in Taipei is a government-owned traditional wet market that was opened in 1907 during the [[Taiwan under Japanese rule|Japanese colonial rule]].<ref name=\"focus\">{{cite news |publisher=[[Focus Taiwan]] |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/business/201910060010 |title=Nanmen Market to close for renovation after 38 years |date=6 October 2019 |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"twt\"/> The market building was demolished in October 2019 and the market temporarily relocated until its replacement modern 12-floor building is completed in 2022.<ref name=\"focus\"/>\n\n===Thailand===\nWet markets are the dominant preferred venue for grocery shopping in [[Thailand]] due to the local importance of fresh food.<ref>{{cite book |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=-A-7d-2VpwcC |page=295 |title= Consumer Behavior and Culture: Consequences for Global Marketing and Advertising  |first=Marieke |last=de Mooij |publisher=[[Chronicle Books]] |year=2003|isbn=9780761926689 }}</ref>\n\n===Vietnam===\nIn 2017, there were approximately 9,000 wet markets, 800 supermarkets, 160 shopping malls and 1.3 million small family-owned stores across [[Vietnam]] according to government estimates.<ref name=\"vne\">{{cite news |url=https://e.vnexpress.net/news/travel-life/a-hanoi-wet-market-at-the-crossroads-of-modernity-3588516.html |publisher=[[VnExpress]] |title=A Hanoi wet market at the crossroads of modernity |last=Yen |first=Bao |date=12 June 2017 |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, the [[Hanoi]] city government planned to renovate the city's wet markets and transform them into modern shopping malls.<ref name=\"vne\"/> The plan was met with resistance from wet market vendors in 2017 after significant declines in sales figures from other markets that were moved to the basements of high-end shopping centers.<ref name=\"vne\"/>\n\nIn 2020, [[Prime Minister of Vietnam]] [[Nguy\u1ec5n Xu\u00e2n Ph\u00fac]] announced proposals to ban wildlife trade in Vietnam.<ref name=\":1\">\n\n== Health concerns ==\nIf [[sanitation]] standards are not maintained, wet markets containing wildlife products can spread [[disease]]s. Because of the openness, newly introduced animals may come in direct contact with sales clerks, butchers, and customers. Insects such as [[flies]] have relatively easy access to the food products. The [[Influenza A virus subtype H5N1|avian flu]] and [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS]] outbreaks can be traced to keeping live animals in wet markets where the potential for zoonotic transmission is greatly increased.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2020/02/05/802938289/new-coronavirus-wont-be-the-last-outbreak-to-move-from-animal-to-human |title=New Coronavirus 'Won't Be the Last' Outbreak to Move from Animal to Human |department=Goats and Soda |publisher=[[NPR]] |date=2020-02-05 |accessdate=2020-02-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2020/jan/24/calls-for-global-ban-wild-animal-markets-amid-coronavirus-outbreak |title=Calls for global ban on wild animal markets amid coronavirus outbreak |date=2020-01-24 |work=[[The Guardian]] |location=London |accessdate=2020-02-29}}</ref> Wetmarkets were banned from carrying wildlife in Vietnam as a response.<ref name=\":1\" /> Chinese wet markets carrying wildlife had previously been closed in 2003 when they were implicated as playing a central part in the [[2002\u20132004 SARS outbreak]], but had been reopened before being closed in 2020 again.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nWet markets where animals are traded in unsanitary conditions combined with the ability of viruses to undergo fast recombination were pointed out by Chinese scientists as a \"time-bomb\" as early as in 2007.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cheng|first=VC|date=Oct 2007|title=Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome Coronavirus as an Agent of Emerging and Reemerging Infection|journal=Clinical Microbiology Reviews|volume=20|issue=4|pages=660\u201394|doi=10.1128/CMR.00023-07|pmid=17934078|pmc=2176051|quote=}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote|text=Large numbers and varieties of these wild game mammals in overcrowded cages and the lack of biosecurity measures in wet markets allowed the jumping of this novel virus from animals to human. (...) Coronaviruses are well known to undergo genetic recombination, which may lead to new genotypes and outbreaks. The presence of a large reservoir of SARS-CoV-like viruses in horseshoe bats, together with the culture of eating exotic mammals in southern China, is a time bomb.|author=VC Cheng|title=|source=Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome Coronavirus as an Agent of Emerging and Reemerging Infection}}\n\nChinese epidemiology experts Zhong Nanshan, Guan Yi and Yuen Kwok-yung have called for closure of wet markets since 2010.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/comment/opinion/article/3047828/first-sars-now-wuhan-coronavirus-heres-why-china-should-ban-its|title=Wuhan coronavirus another reason to ban China's wildlife trade forever|date=2020-01-29|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\nAmidst the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2020 coronavirus pandemic]], Chinese wet markets have been again blamed for the outbreak by Chinese scientists<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/3047087/china-has-been-transparent-about-wuhan-outbreak-virus-expert|title=China has been transparent about Wuhan outbreak, virus expert says|date=2020-01-22|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/3047238/why-wild-animals-are-key-ingredient-chinas-coronavirus-outbreak|title=Why wild animals are a key ingredient in China's coronavirus outbreak|date=2020-01-22|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> and global criticisms followed.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Spinney|first=Laura|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/28/is-factory-farming-to-blame-for-coronavirus|title=Is factory farming to blame for coronavirus?|date=2020-03-28|work=The Observer|quote=Most of the attention so far has been focused on the interface between humans and the intermediate host, with fingers of blame being pointed at Chinese wet markets and eating habits,...|access-date=2020-03-30|language=en-GB|issn=0029-7712}}</ref> Some reports say wildlife markets in other countries of Asia,<ref name=\"sierraclub.org\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://9now.nine.com.au/60-minutes/coronavirus-expert-shut-down-of-asias-wet-wildlife-markets-60-minutes/f7f7781f-8e44-4eb8-9704-804b1e1680ca|title=Coronavirus expert calls for shut down of Asia's wildlife markets|last=|first=|date=|website=Nine News Australia|language=en-AU|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5797739/wild-animals-markets-coronavirus/|title=Don't Blame China. The Next Pandemic Could Come From Anywhere|last=|first=|date=|website=Time|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> Africa,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wildaid.org/africa-risks-virus-outbreak-from-wildlife-trade/|title=Africa Risks Virus Outbreak From Wildlife Trade|date=2020-02-28|website=WildAid|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref name=\"dailymaverick\">{{cite news|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2020-03-02-a-sea-change-in-chinas-attitude-towards-wildlife-exploitation-may-just-save-the-planet/|title=A sea change in China's attitude towards wildlife exploitation may just save the planet|date=2020-03-02|newspaper=Daily Maverick|quote=Knights hoped China would also play a role to help \u201ccountries around the world. It\u2019s no good simply banning the trade in China. The same risks are very much out there in Asia as well as Africa.\u201d}}</ref><ref name=\"indiamongabay\">{{cite news|url=https://india.mongabay.com/2020/03/commentary-crackdown-on-wet-markets-and-illegal-wildlife-trade-could-prevent-the-next-pandemic/|title=Crackdown on wet markets and illegal wildlife trade could prevent the next pandemic|date=2020-03-25|newspaper=Mongabay India|quote=...what we do know is that wet markets such as Wuhan, and for that matter Agartala\u2019s Golbazar or the thousands such that exist in Asia and Africa allow for easy transmission of viruses and other pathogens from animals to humans.}}</ref> and in general all over the world are also similarly prone to health risks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statesman.com/news/20200326/fact-check-is-chinese-culture-to-blame-for-coronavirus|title=Fact-check: Is Chinese culture to blame for the coronavirus?|last=Mekelburg|first=Madlin|website=Austin American-Statesman|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> In April 2020, Anthony Fauci called for the international community to force the closure of wet markets due to the human-animal interface and potential for zoonotic diseases.<ref name=\"Politico\" />\n\n==Economic role==\nWet markets are less dependent on imported goods than [[supermarket]]s due to their smaller volumes and lesser emphasis on consistency.<ref name=\"ATH-12\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=urH_3knhcjAC&dq|title=Agricultural Trade Highlights|publisher=[[Foreign Agricultural Service]]|year=1994|page=12}}</ref> Researchers have highlighted the lower prices, greater freshness of food, negotiation opportunities, and social interaction spaces as key reasons for the persistence of wet markets.<ref name=\"ZSCSH\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bougoure|first=Ursula|last2=Lee|first2=Bernard|year=2009|editor-last=Lindgreen|editor-first=Adam|title=Service quality in Hong Kong: wet markets vs supermarkets|journal=British Food Journal|language=en|volume=111|issue=1|pages=70\u201379|doi=10.1108/00070700910924245|issn=0007-070X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mele|first=Christopher|last2=Ng|first2=Megan|last3=Chim|first3=May Bo|year=2015|title=Urban markets as a 'corrective' to advanced urbanism: The social space of wet markets in contemporary Singapore|journal=Urban Studies|language=en|volume=52|issue=1|pages=103\u2013120|doi=10.1177/0042098014524613|issn=0042-0980}}</ref><ref name=\"Reuters\" />\n\nThe persistence of wet markets has been attributed to \"culinary traditions that call for freshly slaughtered meat and fish as opposed to frozen meats\",<ref name=\"Reuters\" /> and has been described as \"critical for ensuring urban [[food security]]\",<ref name=\"Morales-2009\" /><ref name=\"Morales-2011\" /> particularly in Chinese cities.<ref name=\"ZSCSH\" /> The influence of wet markets on urban food security include food pricing and physical accessibility.<ref name=\"ZSCSH\" />\n\n==Media coverage==\n<!-- This section is for content *about* media coverage of wet markets, not content *from* media coverage of wet markets -->\nIn [[Western media]] wet markets are often portrayed without distinguishing between general wet markets and wildlife markets, using montages images from different markets across China without specific identifying information.<ref name=\"lynteris-fearnley\">{{cite web|url=https://theconversation.com/why-shutting-down-chinese-wet-markets-could-be-a-terrible-mistake-130625|title=Why shutting down Chinese 'wet markets' could be a terrible mistake|last1=Lynteris|first1=Christos|last2=Fearnley|first2=Lyle|date=2 March 2020|publisher=[[The Conversation (website)|The Conversation]]|accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"lat\">{{cite news|last=St. Cavendish|first=Christopher|url=https://www.latimes.com/food/story/2020-03-11/coronavirus-china-wet-markets|title=No, China's fresh food markets did not cause coronavirus|date=11 March 2020|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref> These depictions have been criticized as exaggerated and [[Orientalism|Orientalist]], and have been blamed for fueling [[Sinophobia]] and \"Chinese otherness\".<ref name=\"lynteris-fearnley\"/><ref name=\"lat\"/><ref name=\"FP\"/>\n\nSince the outbreak of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], media reports urging for permanent blanket bans on all wet markets\u2014as opposed to solely wildlife markets\u2014have been criticized by two anthropologists for undermining the epidemiological need to be specific about the particular species contained in the Huanan Seafood Wholesale Market potentially at the origin of the pandemic.<ref name=\"lynteris-fearnley\"/>\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nImage:Wet market in Tekka Centre, Singapore - 20030228.jpg|Wet market in Tekka Center, [[Singapore]]\nImage:HK SYP Market 60402.jpg|Indoor wet market in Hong Kong\nImage:E8975-Namdaemun-ginseng-and-matsutake-shop.jpg|Live turtles next to pickled ginseng in [[Namdaemun Market]], [[Seoul]]\nImage:Lok_fu_centre_wet_market.jpg|Indoor wet market under Lok Fu Shopping Centre in Hong Kong\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Artisanal food]]\n* [[Asian supermarket]]\n* [[Bazaar]]\n* [[Farmers' market]]\n* [[Palengke]]\n* [[Pasar malam]]\n* [[Pasar pagi]]\n* [[Souk]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Wet markets}}\n{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/gallery/2009/may/15/china-animalwelfare-cat | location=London | work=The Guardian | title=Conservation (Environment), Wildlife (Environment), World news, China (News), Animal welfare (News), Food (impact of production on environment), Animals (News), Ethical and green living (Environment), Environment, Chinese food and drink, Asia Pacific (News) | date=15 May 2009}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n\n[[Category:Food markets]]\n[[Category:Retail markets]]\n[[Category:Vegetables]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Market selling perishable goods, generally including produce, meat, or food animals}}\n{{Chinese|pic=WetmarketHK.jpg|picsize=250px|c=[[wiktionary:\u8857\u5e02|\u8857\u5e02]]|j=gaai<sup>1</sup> si<sup>5</sup>|l=street market|showflag=j|ci={{IPAc-yue|g|aai|1|.|s|i|5}}}}\n<!-- \"\u8857\u5e02\" only means \"wet market\" in Cantonese, so pinyin here is unnecessary -->\n\nA '''wet market''' (also called a '''public market''')<ref name=\"ZSCSH\">{{Cite journal|last=Zhong|first=Taiyang|last2=Si|first2=Zhenzhong|last3=Crush|first3=Jonathan|last4=Scott|first4=Steffanie|last5=Huang|first5=Xianjin|year=2019|title=Achieving urban food security through a hybrid public-private food provisioning system: the case of Nanjing, China|journal=Food Security|language=en|volume=11|issue=5|pages=1071\u20131086|doi=10.1007/s12571-019-00961-8|issn=1876-4517}}</ref><ref name=\"Morales-2009\">{{Cite journal|last=Morales|first=Alfonso|year=2009|title=Public Markets as Community Development Tools|journal=Journal of Planning Education and Research|language=en|volume=28|issue=4|pages=426\u2013440|doi=10.1177/0739456X08329471|issn=0739-456X}}</ref><ref name=\"Morales-2011\">{{Cite journal|last=Morales|first=Alfonso|year=2011|title=Marketplaces: Prospects for Social, Economic, and Political Development|journal=Journal of Planning Literature|language=en|volume=26|issue=1|pages=3\u201317|doi=10.1177/0885412210388040|issn=0885-4122}}</ref> is a [[marketplace]] selling fresh meat, fish, [[greengrocer|produce]], and other perishable goods as distinguished from \"dry markets\" that sell durable goods such as fabric and electronics.<ref>Wholesale Markets: Planning and Design Manual (Fao Agricultural Services Bulletin) (No 90)</ref><ref name=\"OED\">{{cite web |url=https://www.oed.com/view/Entry/227970 |title=wet, adj. |publisher=[[Oxford English Dictionary]] |quote=wet market  n. South-East Asian a market for the sale of fresh meat, fish, and produce  |accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"brown\">{{Cite journal|last=Brown|first=Allison|year=2001|title=Counting Farmers Markets|journal=Geographical Review|volume=91|issue=4|pages=655\u2013674|doi=10.2307/3594724|jstor=3594724}}</ref> The term wet market is often used to signify a '''live animal market''' that slaughters animals upon customer purchase.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Woo|first=Patrick CY|last2=Lau|first2=Susanna KP|last3=Yuen|first3=Kwok-yung|year=2006|title=Infectious diseases emerging from Chinese wet-markets: zoonotic origins of severe respiratory viral infections|journal=Current Opinion in Infectious Diseases|language=en|volume=19|issue=5|pages=401\u2013407|doi=10.1097/01.qco.0000244043.08264.fc|pmid=16940861|issn=0951-7375}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Wan|first=X.F.|year=2012|title=Lessons from Emergence of A/Goose/Guangdong/1996-Like H5N1 Highly Pathogenic Avian Influenza Viruses and Recent Influenza Surveillance Efforts in Southern China: Lessons from Gs/Gd/96-like H5N1 HPAIVs|journal=Zoonoses and Public Health|language=en|volume=59|pages=32\u201342|doi=10.1111/j.1863-2378.2012.01497.x|pmc=4119829|pmid=22958248}}</ref> Wet markets are common throughout the world.<ref name=\"nw\">{{cite news |url=https://www.newsweek.com/peta-launches-petition-close-wet-markets-coronavirus-1494803 |publisher=[[Newsweek]] |title= PETA LAUNCHES PETITION TO SHUT DOWN LIVE ANIMAL MARKETS THAT BREED DISEASES LIKE COVID-19 |first=Khaleda |last=Rahman |date=28 March 2020 |accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Reardon|first=Thomas|last2=Timmer|first2=C. Peter|last3=Minten|first3=Bart|date=2012-07-31|title=Supermarket revolution in Asia and emerging development strategies to include small farmers|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America|volume=109|issue=31|pages=12332\u201312337|doi=10.1073/pnas.1003160108|issn=0027-8424|pmc=3412023|pmid=21135250|bibcode=2012PNAS..10912332R}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2020/01/29/800725826/why-wet-markets-are-the-perfect-place-to-spread-disease|title=Why Wet Markets Are The Perfect Place To Spread Disease|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> Wet markets include a wide variety of markets, such as [[farmers' market]]s, [[fish market]]s, and [[Wildlife trade|wildlife market]]s.<ref name=\"ZSCSH\"/><ref name=\"lynteris-fearnley\"/> \n\nWet markets containing live animals, especially those which combine domesticated and wild animals, but also those which carry wildlife products have been linked to outbreaks of [[zoonotic disease]]s including [[coronavirus disease 2019]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"ZSCSH\"/><ref name=\":2\" /> Not all wet markets carry living animals or wildlife.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"ZSCSH\" /><ref name=\"lynteris-fearnley\"/> Wet markets were banned from holding wildlife in China in 2003, after the [[2002\u20132004 SARS outbreak]], which was directly tied to such practices.<ref name=\":2\" /> Such regulations were lifted before being put into place again in 2020,<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/74f1b26e-53c0-11ea-90ad-25e377c0ee1f|title=Coronavirus piles pressure on China's exotic animal trade|last=Yu|first=Sun|last2=Liu|first2=Xinning|date=2020-02-23|website=Financial Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> with other countries proposing similar bans.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/eba067c4-69ce-11ea-800d-da70cff6e4d3|title=The economic case for ending wildlife trade hits home in Vietnam|last=Reed|first=John|date=2020-03-19|website=Financial Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\nMedia reports that fail to distinguish between all wet markets from those with live produce or wildlife have been blamed for fueling [[List of incidents of xenophobia and racism related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|xenophobia related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=\"FP\">{{cite news |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/01/27/coronavirus-covid19-dont-blame-bat-soup-for-the-virus/ |publisher=[[Foreign Policy]] |title=Don't Blame Bat Soup for the Coronavirus |last=Palmer |first=James |date=27 January 2020 |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"lynteris-fearnley\"/>\n\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n==Terminology==\nAs early as 1948, \"wet market\" was identified as a name in English for a type of market.<ref name=\"IRCD\">{{cite web|url=https://northeastiowarcd.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/IA-FM-Chapter-1.pdf|title=Chapter 1: What is a Farmer's Market?|publisher=Northeast Iowa Resource Conservation & Development|accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref> The term \"wet market\" originated from [[Hong Kong English]] and entered the ''[[Oxford English Dictionary]]'' in 2016.<ref name=\":5\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/may/13/east-asian-words-oxford-english-dictionary-hong-kong-singapore-oed|title=East Asian words make it into ''Oxford English Dictionary''|date=13 May 2016|work=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=22 May 2018|agency=[[Agence France-Presse]]|location=London}}</ref>\n\nThe \"wet\" in \"wet market\" refers to the constantly wet floors as a consequence of the spraying of fresh produce and cleaning of meat and seafood stalls.<ref>{{cite book|last=Burton|first=Dawn|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hiFxfmZteFgC|title=Cross-Cultural Marketing: Theory, Practice and Relevance|publisher=[[Routledge]]|year=2008|isbn=9781134060177|page=146}}</ref><ref name=\"Reuters\" /> Sometimes, the term wet market is used to signify a live animal market that sells directly to consumers.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\" />\n\n===Synonyms===\nThe term \"public market\" is synonymous with \"wet market\",<ref name=\"ZSCSH\"/><ref name=\"Morales-2009\"/><ref name=\"Morales-2011\"/> although it may sometimes refer exclusively to state-owned and community-owned wet markets.<ref name=\"ZSCSH\"/><ref name=\"Morales-2009\"/><ref name=\"Morales-2011\"/>\n\nWet markets may also be called \"fresh food markets\" and \"good food markets\" when referring to markets consisting of numerous competing vendors primarily selling fruits and vegetables.<ref name=\"brown\" />\n\n==Around the world==\nThe term \"wet market\", which specifies markets that sell fresh produce and meat, includes a broad variety of markets.<ref name=\"ZSCSH\" /><ref name=\"lynteris-fearnley\" /> Wet markets can be categorized according to their ownership structure ([[Privately held company|privately owned]], [[State-owned enterprise|state-owned]], or [[Community ownership|community-owned]]), scale ([[Wholesaling|wholesale]] or [[retail]]), and produce (vegetables, slaughtered meat, live animals).<ref name=\"ZSCSH\" /><ref name=\"lynteris-fearnley\" /> They can be further subcategorized based on whether the meat sold comes from [[Domestication of animals|domesticated]] or [[wildlife|wild animal]]s.<ref name=\"ZSCSH\" /><ref name=\"lynteris-fearnley\" />\n\n=== China ===\n[[File:Seafood section of Sanqi Baihui Market, Hall 1 (20190519152946).jpg|thumb|Seafood section of Sanqi Baihui Market in [[Beijing]], [[China]]]]\nAs of 2018, wet markets remain the most prevalent food outlet in urban regions of China despite the rise of supermarket chains since the 1990s.<ref name=\"sustainability-2018\">{{Cite journal |last=Zhong |first=Taiyang |last2=Si |first2=Zhenzhong |last3=Crush |first3=Jonathan |last4=Xu |first4=Zhiying |last5=Huang |first5=Xianjin |last6=Scott |first6=Steffanie |last7=Tang |first7=Shuangshuang |last8=Zhang |first8=Xiang |year=2018 |title=The Impact of Proximity to Wet Markets and Supermarkets on Household Dietary Diversity in Nanjing City, China |url=http://www.mdpi.com/2071-1050/10/5/1465 |journal=Sustainability |language=en |volume=10 |issue=5 |pages=1465 |doi=10.3390/su10051465 |issn=2071-1050}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, all roadside markets in [[Hangzhou]] were banned and moved indoors.<ref name=\"SD-Hangzhou\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.shine.cn/feature/travel/1805315493/ |publisher=[[Shanghai Daily]] |title=Regeneration and reinvention of Hangzhou's wet markets |last=Jia |first=Shi |date=31 May 2018 |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> In 2003, wet markets across China were banned from holding wildlife after the 2002\u20132004 SARS outbreak, which was directly tied to such practices.<ref name=\":2\" /> In 2014, live poultry was banned from all markets in Hangzhou due to the [[Influenza A virus subtype H7N9#Reported cases in 2013|H7N9 avian influenza outbreak]].<ref name=\"SD-Hangzhou\"/\n\nDuring the 2010s, \"smart markets\" equipped with e-payment terminals emerged as traditional wet markets faced increasing competition from discount stores.<ref name=\"SD-Hangzhou\"/>\n\nThe origin of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was linked to the [[Huanan Seafood Wholesale Market]] in [[Wuhan]], [[China]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uchicagomedicine.org/forefront/prevention-and-screening-articles/wuhan-coronavirus|title=COVID-19: What we know so far about the 2019 novel coronavirus|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Following the outbreak, proposals were made to ban the operation of wet markets selling wild animals for human consumption.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=http://cbc.ca/radio/thecurrent/the-current-for-feb-17-2020-1.5466207/experts-call-for-global-ban-on-live-animal-markets-wildlife-trade-amidst-coronavirus-outbreak-1.5466219|title=Experts call for global ban on live animal markets, wildlife trade amidst coronavirus outbreak|date=February 17, 2020|work=CBC|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{citation|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2020/jan/24/calls-for-global-ban-wild-animal-markets-amid-coronavirus-outbreak|publisher=The Guardian|date=24 January 2020|title=Calls for global ban on wild animal markets amid coronavirus outbreak|author=Sarah Boseley}}</ref> A few others have pointed out that most wet markets in China do not sell wild animals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://radiichina.com/wet-markets-wild-animals-china/|title=No, You Won't Find \"Wild Animals\" in Most of China's Wet Markets|last=Bossons|first=Matthew|date=2020-02-25|website=RADII|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theconversation.com/why-shutting-down-chinese-wet-markets-could-be-a-terrible-mistake-130625|title=Why shutting down Chinese 'wet markets' could be a terrible mistake|last=Lynteris|first=Christos|last2=Fearnley|first2=Lyle|website=The Conversation|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\nThe Huanan Seafood Wholesale Market was shut down on 1 January 2020. The Chinese government subsequently announced a permanent ban on the sale of wild animal products at wet markets.<ref name=\"sierraclub.org\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sierraclub.org/sierra/china-could-end-global-trade-wildlife|title=China Could End the Global Trade in Wildlife|date=2020-03-26|website=Sierra Club|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref>{{citation|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/china-bans-wildlife-trade-consumption-coronavirus-2020-2|publisher=Business Insider|date=25 February 2020|title=China just banned the trade and consumption of wild animals. Experts think the coronavirus jumped from live animals to people at a market.|author=Aylin Woodward}}</ref> By {{date|2020-04-02|DMY}}, some temporarily closed wet markets in China were reported to have been reopened, leading to public criticism of the Chinese government's handling of wild animal trade by [[Anthony Fauci]] and [[Lindsey Graham]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=O'reilly|first=Andrew|url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/lindsey-graham-asks-china-to-close-all-operating-wet-markets-after-coronavirus-outbreak|title=Lindsey Graham asks China to close 'all operating wet markets' after coronavirus outbreak|date=2020-04-02|work=Fox News|access-date=2020-04-03|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Bowden|first=John|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/senate/490834-graham-asks-colleagues-to-support-call-for-china-to-close-wet-markets|title=Graham asks colleagues to support call for China to close wet markets|date=2020-04-02|work=The Hill|access-date=2020-04-03|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Politico\">{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/04/03/anthony-fauci-foreign-wet-markets-shutdown-162975 |title='Shut down those things right away': Calls to close 'wet markets' ramp up pressure on China |first=Quint |last=Forgey |date=3 April 2020 |work=Politico |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Hong Kong ====\n[[File:HK Bridges Street Market.JPG|thumb|The building that housed the former [[Bridges Street Market]] in [[Hong Kong]]]]\nIn 1920, the Reclamation Street Market was opened in [[Hong Kong]]. Due to structure problems, Reclamation Street Market was removed by the government in 1953.<ref>{{Cite book|title=\u7b2c\u4e8c\u5c46\u5eff\u4e00\u4e16\u7d00\u83ef\u4eba\u5730\u5340\u6b77\u53f2\u6559\u80b2\u8ad6\u6587\u96c6|trans-title=Second Collection of Historical Education Papers on Chinese in the 21st Century |author=Bao Shaolin|publisher=Zhonghua Book Company (Hong Kong) Limited.|year=2012|language=Chinese|isbn=|location=|pages=332}}</ref> In 1957, Yau Ma Tei Street Market launched to replace the Reclamation Street Market.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mmis.hkpl.gov.hk/coverpage/-/coverpage/view?p_r_p_-1078056564_c=QF757YsWv59a9PNz3lScYjii24oro5jB&_coverpage_WAR_mmisportalportlet_o=18&_coverpage_WAR_mmisportalportlet_actual_q=%28%20%28%20allTermsMandatory%3A%28true%29%20OR+all_dc.title%3A%28%E6%B2%B9%E9%BA%BB%E5%9C%B0%E8%A1%97%E5%B8%82%29%20OR+all_dc.creator%3A%28%E6%B2%B9%E9%BA%BB%E5%9C%B0%E8%A1%97%E5%B8%82%29%20OR+all_dc.contributor%3A%28%E6%B2%B9%E9%BA%BB%E5%9C%B0%E8%A1%97%E5%B8%82%29%20OR+all_dc.subject%3A%28%E6%B2%B9%E9%BA%BB%E5%9C%B0%E8%A1%97%E5%B8%82%29%20OR+fulltext%3A%28%E6%B2%B9%E9%BA%BB%E5%9C%B0%E8%A1%97%E5%B8%82%29%20OR+all_dc.description%3A%28%E6%B2%B9%E9%BA%BB%E5%9C%B0%E8%A1%97%E5%B8%82%29%20%29%20%29&_coverpage_WAR_mmisportalportlet_sort_order=desc&_coverpage_WAR_mmisportalportlet_sort_field=score&_coverpage_WAR_mmisportalportlet_log=Y|title=\u6cb9\u9ebb\u5730\u65b0\u5efa\u8857\u5e02\u6628\u6668\u958b\u5e55\u5f8c\u71df\u696d|trans-title=Yau Ma Tei New Market opened after opening yesterday morning|language=Chinese|last=|first=|date=1957-11-02|work=Hong Kong Business Daily|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref> There were fixed-pitch stalls which sold vegetables, fruits, seafood, beef, pork, and poultry. Also, there were stalls selling baby chickens, baby ducks, and three-striped box turtles as pets.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hkmemory.hk/collections/oral_history/All_Items_OH/oha_70/records/index.html|title=Yau Ma Tei's wet markets in the early post-war period|date=2011-03-29|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref>\n\nCentral Market was launched on 16 May 1842. Its position was central, on Queen's Road. In this market, people could find all kinds of meat, fruit and vegetables, poultry, salt fish, fresh fish, weighing rooms and money changers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sunzi.lib.hku.hk/hkgro/view/g1842/728468.pdf|title=The Friend Of China, and Hong Kong Gazette|date=1842-05-12|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref>\n\nIn Hong Kong, wet markets are most frequented by older residents, those with lower incomes, and domestic helpers who serve approximately 10 percent of Hong Kong's residents.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emeraldinsight.com/journals.htm?articleid=1412265&show=abstract |title=EmeraldInsight |website=EmeraldInsight.com |accessdate=2016-08-01}}</ref> Wet markets have become destinations for tourists to \"see the real Hong Kong\".<ref>{{cite news| url=http://intransit.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/03/18/a-guide-to-hong-kongs-wet-markets/ | newspaper=[[The New York Times]] | first=Sei | last=Chong | title=A Guide to Hong Kong's Wet Markets | date=18 March 2011|accessdate=2016-08-01}}</ref> Many of the wet market buildings are owned by property investment firms and as a result the price of food can vary from market to market.<ref>{{cite news|author=Elmer W. Cagape |url=http://asiancorrespondent.com/64501/expensive-food-tung-chung-hk/ |title=Tung Chung town pays the most for food in Hong Kong |work=Asian Correspondent |date=2011-09-08 |accessdate=2016-08-01}}</ref>\n\nIn 1994, wet markets accounted for 70% of produce sales and 50% of meat sales in Hong Kong.<ref name=\"ATH-7\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=urH_3knhcjAC&dq |title=Agricultural Trade Highlights |publisher=[[Foreign Agricultural Service]] |year=1994 |page=7}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008 the government of Hong Kong proposed that all poultry should be slaughtered at central abattoirs to combat the spread of [[avian flu]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.news.gov.hk/isd/ebulletin/en/category/issues/080614/html/080613en05005.htm |title=Central abattoir set for 2011 |website=Archive.news.gov.hk |date=2008-06-13 |accessdate=2016-08-01}}</ref>\n\nHong Kong's wet markets use red lampshades to make the food look fresher.<ref>{{cite news|script-title=zh:\u8d85\u5de8\u8857\u5e02\u71c8\u73fe\u8eab\u5546\u5834|trans-title=Super large wet market red lamps appears in shopping mall|url=http://www.sharpdaily.hk/article/news/20120914/134111|accessdate=19 November 2012|newspaper=Sharp Daily|date=14 September 2012|language=Chinese|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121108070308/http://www.sharpdaily.hk/article/news/20120914/134111|archive-date=8 November 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Mexico===\n[[File:Mercado 20 de noviembre - Oaxaca de Ju\u00e1rez - 10.jpg|thumb|Fresh meat section of the Mercado 20 de Noviembre in [[Oaxaca City|Oaxaca]], [[Mexico]]]]\nSome traditional [[Mexico|Mexican]] open-air markets called ''[[tianguis]]'', such as the Mercado Margarita Maza de Ju\u00e1rez in [[Oaxaca City|Oaxaca]], are separated into a wet market (''zona h\u00fameda'') and a dry market (''zona seca'').<ref name=\"imparcial\">{{cite news |url=https://imparcialoaxaca.mx/oaxaca/304648/central-de-abasto-bomba-de-tiempo-y-nido-de-delincuencia/ |title=Central de Abasto: bomba de tiempo y nido de delincuencia |publisher=[[El Imparcial (Oaxaca)]] |date=9 May 2019 |accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Singapore===\nIn the early 1990s, the slaughter of animals was banned in 12 inner-city markets and 22 wet market centers in [[Singapore]].<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RjxIAAAAYAAJ |title=U.S. Trade and Prospects: Dairy, livestock, and poultry products |year=1992 |publisher=The Service |author=United States. Foreign Agricultural Service. Dairy, Livestock, and Poultry Division, United States. World Agricultural Outlook Board |page=3}}</ref> In 2020, the [[National Environment Agency]] issued advisories for \"high standards of hygiene and cleanliness\" for the 83 markets that it oversees.<ref name=\"Reuters\">{{cite news|last=Chandran|first=Rina|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/southeast-asia-health-markets/traditional-markets-blamed-for-virus-outbreak-are-lifeline-for-asias-poor-idUSL8N2A5201|title=Traditional markets blamed for virus outbreak are lifeline for Asia's poor|date=7 February 2020|accessdate=4 April 2020|publisher=[[Reuters]]}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Tekka Centre|Tekka Market]], [[Tiong Bahru#Tiong Bahru Market|Tiong Bahru Market]], and [[Chinatown, Singapore#Geography|Chinatown Complex Market]] are prominent wet markets containing seasonal fruit, fresh vegetables, imported beef, and live seafood.<ref name=\"cnn-sg\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/travel/article/singapore-wet-market/index.html |publisher=[[CNN]] |title=Singapore wet markets: Reminder of bygone days |date=22 June 2015 |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Taiwan===\nIn 1997, a report by the [[Taipei]] city government indicated that the city had 61 major wet markets with almost 10,000 registered vendors.<ref name=\"twt\">{{cite news |url=https://taiwantoday.tw/news.php?post=12589&unit=8,29,32,45 |title=Are Wet Markets Drying Up? |publisher=[[Taiwan Today]] |last=Trappey |first=Charles V. |date=1 March 1997 |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> The report also indicated that most of the city's wet markets were in serious need of repair and that almost 3,500 of the vendor stalls lay vacant.<ref name=\"twt\"/>\n\nThe Nanmen Market in Taipei is a government-owned traditional wet market that was opened in 1907 during the [[Taiwan under Japanese rule|Japanese colonial rule]].<ref name=\"focus\">{{cite news |publisher=[[Focus Taiwan]] |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/business/201910060010 |title=Nanmen Market to close for renovation after 38 years |date=6 October 2019 |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"twt\"/> The market building was demolished in October 2019 and the market temporarily relocated until its replacement modern 12-floor building is completed in 2022.<ref name=\"focus\"/>\n\n===Thailand===\nWet markets are the dominant preferred venue for grocery shopping in [[Thailand]] due to the local importance of fresh food.<ref>{{cite book |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=-A-7d-2VpwcC |page=295 |title= Consumer Behavior and Culture: Consequences for Global Marketing and Advertising  |first=Marieke |last=de Mooij |publisher=[[Chronicle Books]] |year=2003|isbn=9780761926689 }}</ref>\n\n===Vietnam===\nIn 2017, there were approximately 9,000 wet markets, 800 supermarkets, 160 shopping malls and 1.3 million small family-owned stores across [[Vietnam]] according to government estimates.<ref name=\"vne\">{{cite news |url=https://e.vnexpress.net/news/travel-life/a-hanoi-wet-market-at-the-crossroads-of-modernity-3588516.html |publisher=[[VnExpress]] |title=A Hanoi wet market at the crossroads of modernity |last=Yen |first=Bao |date=12 June 2017 |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, the [[Hanoi]] city government planned to renovate the city's wet markets and transform them into modern shopping malls.<ref name=\"vne\"/> The plan was met with resistance from wet market vendors in 2017 after significant declines in sales figures from other markets that were moved to the basements of high-end shopping centers.<ref name=\"vne\"/>\n\nIn 2020, [[Prime Minister of Vietnam]] [[Nguy\u1ec5n Xu\u00e2n Ph\u00fac]] announced proposals to ban wildlife trade in Vietnam.<ref name=\":1\">\n\n== Health concerns ==\nIf [[sanitation]] standards are not maintained, wet markets containing wildlife products can spread [[disease]]s. Because of the openness, newly introduced animals may come in direct contact with sales clerks, butchers, and customers. Insects such as [[flies]] have relatively easy access to the food products. The [[Influenza A virus subtype H5N1|avian flu]] and [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS]] outbreaks can be traced to keeping live animals in wet markets where the potential for zoonotic transmission is greatly increased.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2020/02/05/802938289/new-coronavirus-wont-be-the-last-outbreak-to-move-from-animal-to-human |title=New Coronavirus 'Won't Be the Last' Outbreak to Move from Animal to Human |department=Goats and Soda |publisher=[[NPR]] |date=2020-02-05 |accessdate=2020-02-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2020/jan/24/calls-for-global-ban-wild-animal-markets-amid-coronavirus-outbreak |title=Calls for global ban on wild animal markets amid coronavirus outbreak |date=2020-01-24 |work=[[The Guardian]] |location=London |accessdate=2020-02-29}}</ref> Wetmarkets were banned from carrying wildlife in Vietnam as a response.<ref name=\":1\" /> Chinese wet markets carrying wildlife had previously been closed in 2003 when they were implicated as playing a central part in the [[2002\u20132004 SARS outbreak]], but had been reopened before being closed in 2020 again.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nWet markets where animals are traded in unsanitary conditions combined with the ability of viruses to undergo fast recombination were pointed out by Chinese scientists as a \"time-bomb\" as early as in 2007.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cheng|first=VC|date=Oct 2007|title=Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome Coronavirus as an Agent of Emerging and Reemerging Infection|journal=Clinical Microbiology Reviews|volume=20|issue=4|pages=660\u201394|doi=10.1128/CMR.00023-07|pmid=17934078|pmc=2176051|quote=}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote|text=Large numbers and varieties of these wild game mammals in overcrowded cages and the lack of biosecurity measures in wet markets allowed the jumping of this novel virus from animals to human. (...) Coronaviruses are well known to undergo genetic recombination, which may lead to new genotypes and outbreaks. The presence of a large reservoir of SARS-CoV-like viruses in horseshoe bats, together with the culture of eating exotic mammals in southern China, is a time bomb.|author=VC Cheng|title=|source=Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome Coronavirus as an Agent of Emerging and Reemerging Infection}}\n\nChinese epidemiology experts Zhong Nanshan, Guan Yi and Yuen Kwok-yung have called for closure of wet markets since 2010.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/comment/opinion/article/3047828/first-sars-now-wuhan-coronavirus-heres-why-china-should-ban-its|title=Wuhan coronavirus another reason to ban China's wildlife trade forever|date=2020-01-29|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\nAmidst the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2020 coronavirus pandemic]], Chinese wet markets have been again blamed for the outbreak by Chinese scientists<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/3047087/china-has-been-transparent-about-wuhan-outbreak-virus-expert|title=China has been transparent about Wuhan outbreak, virus expert says|date=2020-01-22|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/3047238/why-wild-animals-are-key-ingredient-chinas-coronavirus-outbreak|title=Why wild animals are a key ingredient in China's coronavirus outbreak|date=2020-01-22|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> and global criticisms followed.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Spinney|first=Laura|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/28/is-factory-farming-to-blame-for-coronavirus|title=Is factory farming to blame for coronavirus?|date=2020-03-28|work=The Observer|quote=Most of the attention so far has been focused on the interface between humans and the intermediate host, with fingers of blame being pointed at Chinese wet markets and eating habits,...|access-date=2020-03-30|language=en-GB|issn=0029-7712}}</ref> Some reports say wildlife markets in other countries of Asia,<ref name=\"sierraclub.org\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://9now.nine.com.au/60-minutes/coronavirus-expert-shut-down-of-asias-wet-wildlife-markets-60-minutes/f7f7781f-8e44-4eb8-9704-804b1e1680ca|title=Coronavirus expert calls for shut down of Asia's wildlife markets|last=|first=|date=|website=Nine News Australia|language=en-AU|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5797739/wild-animals-markets-coronavirus/|title=Don't Blame China. The Next Pandemic Could Come From Anywhere|last=|first=|date=|website=Time|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> Africa,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wildaid.org/africa-risks-virus-outbreak-from-wildlife-trade/|title=Africa Risks Virus Outbreak From Wildlife Trade|date=2020-02-28|website=WildAid|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref name=\"dailymaverick\">{{cite news|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2020-03-02-a-sea-change-in-chinas-attitude-towards-wildlife-exploitation-may-just-save-the-planet/|title=A sea change in China's attitude towards wildlife exploitation may just save the planet|date=2020-03-02|newspaper=Daily Maverick|quote=Knights hoped China would also play a role to help \u201ccountries around the world. It\u2019s no good simply banning the trade in China. The same risks are very much out there in Asia as well as Africa.\u201d}}</ref><ref name=\"indiamongabay\">{{cite news|url=https://india.mongabay.com/2020/03/commentary-crackdown-on-wet-markets-and-illegal-wildlife-trade-could-prevent-the-next-pandemic/|title=Crackdown on wet markets and illegal wildlife trade could prevent the next pandemic|date=2020-03-25|newspaper=Mongabay India|quote=...what we do know is that wet markets such as Wuhan, and for that matter Agartala\u2019s Golbazar or the thousands such that exist in Asia and Africa allow for easy transmission of viruses and other pathogens from animals to humans.}}</ref> and in general all over the world are also similarly prone to health risks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statesman.com/news/20200326/fact-check-is-chinese-culture-to-blame-for-coronavirus|title=Fact-check: Is Chinese culture to blame for the coronavirus?|last=Mekelburg|first=Madlin|website=Austin American-Statesman|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> In April 2020, Anthony Fauci called for the international community to force the closure of wet markets due to the human-animal interface and potential for zoonotic diseases.<ref name=\"Politico\" />\n\n==Economic role==\nWet markets are less dependent on imported goods than [[supermarket]]s due to their smaller volumes and lesser emphasis on consistency.<ref name=\"ATH-12\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=urH_3knhcjAC&dq|title=Agricultural Trade Highlights|publisher=[[Foreign Agricultural Service]]|year=1994|page=12}}</ref> Researchers have highlighted the lower prices, greater freshness of food, negotiation opportunities, and social interaction spaces as key reasons for the persistence of wet markets.<ref name=\"ZSCSH\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bougoure|first=Ursula|last2=Lee|first2=Bernard|year=2009|editor-last=Lindgreen|editor-first=Adam|title=Service quality in Hong Kong: wet markets vs supermarkets|journal=British Food Journal|language=en|volume=111|issue=1|pages=70\u201379|doi=10.1108/00070700910924245|issn=0007-070X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mele|first=Christopher|last2=Ng|first2=Megan|last3=Chim|first3=May Bo|year=2015|title=Urban markets as a 'corrective' to advanced urbanism: The social space of wet markets in contemporary Singapore|journal=Urban Studies|language=en|volume=52|issue=1|pages=103\u2013120|doi=10.1177/0042098014524613|issn=0042-0980}}</ref><ref name=\"Reuters\" />\n\nThe persistence of wet markets has been attributed to \"culinary traditions that call for freshly slaughtered meat and fish as opposed to frozen meats\",<ref name=\"Reuters\" /> and has been described as \"critical for ensuring urban [[food security]]\",<ref name=\"Morales-2009\" /><ref name=\"Morales-2011\" /> particularly in Chinese cities.<ref name=\"ZSCSH\" /> The influence of wet markets on urban food security include food pricing and physical accessibility.<ref name=\"ZSCSH\" />\n\n==Media coverage==\n<!-- This section is for content *about* media coverage of wet markets, not content *from* media coverage of wet markets -->\nIn [[Western media]] wet markets are often portrayed without distinguishing between general wet markets and wildlife markets, using montages images from different markets across China without specific identifying information.<ref name=\"lynteris-fearnley\">{{cite web|url=https://theconversation.com/why-shutting-down-chinese-wet-markets-could-be-a-terrible-mistake-130625|title=Why shutting down Chinese 'wet markets' could be a terrible mistake|last1=Lynteris|first1=Christos|last2=Fearnley|first2=Lyle|date=2 March 2020|publisher=[[The Conversation (website)|The Conversation]]|accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"lat\">{{cite news|last=St. Cavendish|first=Christopher|url=https://www.latimes.com/food/story/2020-03-11/coronavirus-china-wet-markets|title=No, China's fresh food markets did not cause coronavirus|date=11 March 2020|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref> These depictions have been criticized as exaggerated and [[Orientalism|Orientalist]], and have been blamed for fueling [[Sinophobia]] and \"Chinese otherness\".<ref name=\"lynteris-fearnley\"/><ref name=\"lat\"/><ref name=\"FP\"/>\n\nSince the outbreak of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], media reports urging for permanent blanket bans on all wet markets\u2014as opposed to solely wildlife markets\u2014have been criticized by two anthropologists for undermining the epidemiological need to be specific about the particular species contained in the Huanan Seafood Wholesale Market potentially at the origin of the pandemic.<ref name=\"lynteris-fearnley\"/>\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nImage:Wet market in Tekka Centre, Singapore - 20030228.jpg|Wet market in Tekka Center, [[Singapore]]\nImage:HK SYP Market 60402.jpg|Indoor wet market in Hong Kong\nImage:E8975-Namdaemun-ginseng-and-matsutake-shop.jpg|Live turtles next to pickled ginseng in [[Namdaemun Market]], [[Seoul]]\nImage:Lok_fu_centre_wet_market.jpg|Indoor wet market under Lok Fu Shopping Centre in Hong Kong\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Artisanal food]]\n* [[Asian supermarket]]\n* [[Bazaar]]\n* [[Farmers' market]]\n* [[Palengke]]\n* [[Pasar malam]]\n* [[Pasar pagi]]\n* [[Souk]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Wet markets}}\n{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/gallery/2009/may/15/china-animalwelfare-cat | location=London | work=The Guardian | title=Conservation (Environment), Wildlife (Environment), World news, China (News), Animal welfare (News), Food (impact of production on environment), Animals (News), Ethical and green living (Environment), Environment, Chinese food and drink, Asia Pacific (News) | date=15 May 2009}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n\n[[Category:Food markets]]\n[[Category:Retail markets]]\n[[Category:Vegetables]]\n", "name_user": "MarkH21", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eChina:missing angle bracket", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wet_market"}
{"title_page": "Infernal Atrocity", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Infernal Atrocity\n| type       = album\n| artist     = [[Revulsed]]\n| cover      = InfernalAtrocity.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = October 31, 2015\n| recorded   = 2013-2015\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Death metal]], [[brutal death metal]], [[slam death metal]], [[technical death metal]], [[Christian metal]],<ref name=\"Roemers\">{{cite web | url = http://tometal.com/review/revulsed-infernal-atrocity/ | title = Revulsed \u2013 ''Infernal Atrocity'' | last = Roemers | first = Wouter | work = Transcending Obscurity | location = Belgium | year = 2015 | accessdate = October 13, 2016 }}</ref> [[extreme metal]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mauce.nl/site/revulsed-reveals-cover-art-for-debut-album-infernal-atrocity/|title='Revulsed' Reveals Cover Art For Debut Album ''Infernal Atrocity''|publisher=The Metal Resource|author=thrashboy|date=April 30, 2015|accessdate=October 13, 2016}}</ref>\n| length     = 32:27\n| label      = Permeated Records\n| producer   =\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n{{Album reviews\n|rev1 = Fobia Zine\n|rev1score = 8/10<ref name=\"Prepil\"/>\n|rev2 = Extreminal\n|rev2score = 10/10<ref name=\"Extreme\"/>\n}}\n\n'''''Infernal Atrocity''''' is the debut album by [[brutal death metal]] band [[Revulsed]]. \n\n==Rankings==\nRevulsed was featured on No Clean Singing's list at #17,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nocleansinging.com/2015/12/29/listmania-2015-a-year-end-list-from-vonlughlio-part-2/|title=NO CLEAN SINGING \u00bb LISTMANIA 2015: A YEAR-END LIST FROM VONLUGHLIO (PART 2)|publisher=No Clean Singing|author=Islander|date=December 29, 2015|accessdate=April 4, 2016}}</ref> on Trevor Strnad of [[The Black Dahlia Murder (band)|The Black Dahlia Murder]]'s at #8 out of 100,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metalinjection.net/editorials/the-obituarist/trevor-of-the-black-dahlia-murders-top-100-albums-of-2015|title=Trevor of the Black Dahlia Murders Top 100 albums of 2015|publisher=Metal Injection|first=Trevor|last=Strnad|date=December 30, 2015|accessdate=April 4, 2016}}</ref> and #9 out of 10 on It Djents.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itdjents.com/features/top-10-albums-of-the-year-sean-messier/|title=Top 10 Albums of the Year: Sean Messier|publisher=It Djents|first=Sean|last=Messier|date=December 14, 2015|accessdate=October 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n\"''Infernal Atrocity'' is one of the best contemporary death metal albums... The album, bland title notwithstanding, is traditional in spirit and approach, but contemporary and cutting-edge on all other fronts. It is a welcome return for Jayson Sherlock who managed in transcending obscurity after the demise of [[Paramaecium]]. With [[Mortification (band)|Mortification]] considered a spent force creatively, it\u2019s heartening to see one of the driving forces behind said band make such a convincing return. Hopefully this translates into opportunities for Revulsed so that they can build their own legacy. ''Infernal Atrocity'' should appeal to modern \u2013 as well as traditional genre fans.\" writes Wouter Roemers.<ref name=\"Roemers\"/>  Czech reviewer Prepil rated it as 8 out of 10 and explained, after being translated \"And I'm glad I by chance stumbled on this band, and I think that certainly deserves your attention... [It's] full of brutal, yet dynamic Death Metal, which entertains even during continuous playback..\"<ref name=\"Prepil\">{{cite web | url = http://www.fobiazine.net/article/9123/revulsed--infernal-atrocity-/ | title = Revulsed \u2013 ''Infernal Atrocity'' | last = Prepil | first = | work = Fobia Zine | language = Czech | date = 3 December 2015 | accessdate = October 13, 2016 }}</ref> \"a musical, colorful, varied, extremely hard and content enjoyable profound album.\" writes Daniel F. originally in German.<ref name=\"Daniel F\">{{cite web | url = http://www.whiskey-soda.de/review.php?id=37231 | title = Revulsed \u2013 ''Infernal Atrocity'' | last = F | first = Daniel | work = Whiskey Soda | language = German | date = November 2015 | accessdate = October 13, 2016 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160417004441/http://www.whiskey-soda.de/review.php?id=37231 | archive-date = April 17, 2016 | url-status = dead }}</ref> Batu Cetin reports \"This album 2015 new album is considered that the end to be correct, the Australian group actually old mortification group of drummer Jason Sherlock's considered a new group of connoisseurs know 90 s [[Nuclear Blast Records]] former death metal legends Blaster Group mortification then, but this group Revulsed flour that has no relevance former group mortification la the album is really good, especially the album tons of mix master s etc perfect, there Konner we know from vocal Defeated Sanity, arrangement of parts and especially drummer Jason s distinctive style is recognized directly, so head pressing, the mid-tempo, blast heat and without full gas one of the last period in the best album you want to listen to an album cover one of the best cover is made by Par Olofsson and I think it did, we can summarize this group as formerly had a group legend is an American Gutted -Bleed for us tol with ive- called legendary album this is not the same style, but an overwhelming Revulsed groups, and that the gas full power, after listening to this album gutted I will understand what I mean who know very well. 32 minutes and 9-track album from start to finish is very energetic, especially 2. introduction of Part - agonizing Putrid Self Infliction's - and 3 part input pestilential Articulation head broke waving the neck, the kind that breaks the head, albums, those who miss the sound of bass guitar like me, this album grains bass guitar, guitar, and drums will be able to hear what is playing pleasure.\"<ref name=\"Extreme\">{{cite web|url=http://www.extreminal.com/extreminal/kritik.asp?id=1399|title=Revulsed - ''Infernal Atrocity''||publisher=Extreminal|first=Batu|last=Cetin|date=May 5, 2016|accessdate=October 13, 2016|language=Turkish}}</ref> \"A throwback to early 90s death metal. This album sounds like a lost [[Suffocation (band)|Suffocation]] album that came right after \"Effigy of the Forgotten\". In fact, some of the riffs can be almost directly compared, like the intro to 'Enticement To Carnivorous Impoverishment' is almost identical to the intro to the song 'Breeding The Spawn'. But despite the lack of originality, this album has many great riffs, its a great performance, the production quality is clear (although like other early 90s metal, not as polished as it can be made now), and I'm still giving it a thumbs up. I guess many of the people in this band came from the new defunct InExordium, which was also all about recreating that origins of death metal sound, so in that respect, they have done a great job.\" writes Soul Killer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soulkillerwebzine.com/reviews/r.htm#REVULSED|title=Revulsed - ''Infernal Atrocity''|publisher=Soul Killer|accessdate=October 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{track listing\n| all_writing = \n| title1 = Rapacious Engorgement\n| length1 = 3:57\n| title2 = Agonizing Putrid Self-Infliction\n| length2 = 3:50\n| title3 = Pestilential Articulation\n| length3 = 3:39\n| title4 = Imposed Cognitive Reconstruction\n| length4 = 4:00\n| title5 = Transmutational Crainiotomy\n| length5 = 3:54\n| title6 = Archetypal Cauterization\n| length6 = 4:13\n| title7 = Enticement to Carnivorous Impoverishment\n| length7 = 4:04\n| title8 = Celestial Perspicacity\n| length8 = 2:49\n| title9 = Infernal Atrocity\n| length9 = 2:01\n| title10 = \n| length10 = \n| title11 = \n| length11 = \n| title12 = \n| length12 = \n| title13 = \n| length13 = \n| title14 = \n| length14 = \n| title15 = \n| length15 = \n| title16 = \n| length16 = \n| title17 = \n| length17 = \n| title18 = \n| length18 = \n| title19 = \n| length19 = \n| title20 = \n| length20 = \n| total_length = \n}}\n\n==Personnel==\n;Revulsed\n* Konni L\u00fchring - Vocals\n* Sheldon D'Costa - Guitar, Bass, Mixing, Mastering\n* [[Jayson Sherlock]] - Drums, Mixing, Mastering, Layout\n\n;Production\n* [[Metanoia (metal band)|Yowie Smith]] - Songwriting\n* [[P\u00e4r Olofsson]] - Artwork\n* J\u00f6rg Uken - Recording (Vocals)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2015 debut albums]]\n[[Category:Revulsed albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Infernal Atrocity\n| type       = album\n| artist     = [[Revulsed]]\n| cover      = InfernalAtrocity.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = October 31, 2015\n| recorded   = 2013-2015\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Death metal]], [[brutal death metal]], [[slam death metal]], [[technical death metal]], [[Christian metal]],<ref name=\"Roemers\">{{cite web | url = http://tometal.com/review/revulsed-infernal-atrocity/ | title = Revulsed \u2013 ''Infernal Atrocity'' | last = Roemers | first = Wouter | work = Transcending Obscurity | location = Belgium | year = 2015 | accessdate = October 13, 2016 }}</ref> [[extreme metal]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mauce.nl/site/revulsed-reveals-cover-art-for-debut-album-infernal-atrocity/|title='Revulsed' Reveals Cover Art For Debut Album ''Infernal Atrocity''|publisher=The Metal Resource|author=thrashboy|date=April 30, 2015|accessdate=October 13, 2016}}</ref>\n| length     = 32:27\n| label      = Permeated Records\n| producer   =\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n{{Album reviews\n|rev1 = Fobia Zine\n|rev1score = 8/10<ref name=\"Prepil\"/>\n|rev2 = Extreminal\n|rev2score = 10/10<ref name=\"Extreme\"/>\n}}\n\n'''''Infernal Atrocity''''' is the debut album by [[brutal death metal]] band [[Revulsed]]. \n\n==Rankings==\nRevulsed was featured on No Clean Singing's list at #17,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nocleansinging.com/2015/12/29/listmania-2015-a-year-end-list-from-vonlughlio-part-2/|title=NO CLEAN SINGING \u00bb LISTMANIA 2015: A YEAR-END LIST FROM VONLUGHLIO (PART 2)|publisher=No Clean Singing|author=Islander|date=December 29, 2015|accessdate=April 4, 2016}}</ref> on Trevor Strnad of [[The Black Dahlia Murder (band)|The Black Dahlia Murder]]'s at #8 out of 100,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metalinjection.net/editorials/the-obituarist/trevor-of-the-black-dahlia-murders-top-100-albums-of-2015|title=Trevor of the Black Dahlia Murders Top 100 albums of 2015|publisher=Metal Injection|first=Trevor|last=Strnad|date=December 30, 2015|accessdate=April 4, 2016}}</ref> and #9 out of 10 on It Djents.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itdjents.com/features/top-10-albums-of-the-year-sean-messier/|title=Top 10 Albums of the Year: Sean Messier|publisher=It Djents|first=Sean|last=Messier|date=December 14, 2015|accessdate=October 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n\"''Infernal Atrocity'' is one of the best contemporary death metal albums... The album, bland title notwithstanding, is traditional in spirit and approach, but contemporary and cutting-edge on all other fronts. It is a welcome return for Jayson Sherlock who managed in transcending obscurity after the demise of [[Paramaecium]]. With [[Mortification (band)|Mortification]] considered a spent force creatively, it\u2019s heartening to see one of the driving forces behind said band make such a convincing return. Hopefully this translates into opportunities for Revulsed so that they can build their own legacy. ''Infernal Atrocity'' should appeal to modern \u2013 as well as traditional genre fans.\" writes Wouter Roemers.<ref name=\"Roemers\"/>  Czech reviewer Prepil rated it as 8 out of 10 and explained, after being translated \"And I'm glad I by chance stumbled on this band, and I think that certainly deserves your attention... [It's] full of brutal, yet dynamic Death Metal, which entertains even during continuous playback..\"<ref name=\"Prepil\">{{cite web | url = http://www.fobiazine.net/article/9123/revulsed--infernal-atrocity-/ | title = Revulsed \u2013 ''Infernal Atrocity'' | last = Prepil | first = | work = Fobia Zine | language = Czech | date = 3 December 2015 | accessdate = October 13, 2016 }}</ref> \"a musical, colorful, varied, extremely hard and content enjoyable profound album.\" writes Daniel F. ooriginally in German.<ref name=\"Daniel F\">{{cite web | url = http://www.whiskey-soda.de/review.php?id=37231 | title = Revulsed \u2013 ''Infernal Atrocity'' | last = F | first = Daniel | work = Whiskey Soda | language = German | date = November 2015 | accessdate = October 13, 2016 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160417004441/http://www.whiskey-soda.de/review.php?id=37231 | archive-date = April 17, 2016 | url-status = dead }}</ref> Batu Cetin reports \"This album 2015 new album is considered that the end to be correct, the Australian group actually old mortification group of drummer Jason Sherlock's considered a new group of connoisseurs know 90 s [[Nuclear Blast Records]] former death metal legends Blaster Group mortification then, but this group Revulsed flour that has no relevance former group mortification la the album is really good, especially the album tons of mix master s etc perfect, there Konner we know from vocal Defeated Sanity, arrangement of parts and especially drummer Jason s distinctive style is recognized directly, so head pressing, the mid-tempo, blast heat and without full gas one of the last period in the best album you want to listen to an album cover one of the best cover is made by Par Olofsson and I think it did, we can summarize this group as formerly had a group legend is an American Gutted -Bleed for us tol with ive- called legendary album this is not the same style, but an overwhelming Revulsed groups, and that the gas full power, after listening to this album gutted I will understand what I mean who know very well. 32 minutes and 9-track album from start to finish is very energetic, especially 2. introduction of Part - agonizing Putrid Self Infliction's - and 3 part input pestilential Articulation head broke waving the neck, the kind that breaks the head, albums, those who miss the sound of bass guitar like me, this album grains bass guitar, guitar, and drums will be able to hear what is playing pleasure.\"<ref name=\"Extreme\">{{cite web|url=http://www.extreminal.com/extreminal/kritik.asp?id=1399|title=Revulsed - ''Infernal Atrocity''||publisher=Extreminal|first=Batu|last=Cetin|date=May 5, 2016|accessdate=October 13, 2016|language=Turkish}}</ref> \"A throwback to early 90s death metal. This album sounds like a lost [[Suffocation (band)|Suffocation]] album that came right after \"Effigy of the Forgotten\". In fact, some of the riffs can be almost directly compared, like the intro to 'Enticement To Carnivorous Impoverishment' is almost identical to the intro to the song 'Breeding The Spawn'. But despite the lack of originality, this album has many great riffs, its a great performance, the production quality is clear (although like other early 90s metal, not as polished as it can be made now), and I'm still giving it a thumbs up. I guess many of the people in this band came from the new defunct InExordium, which was also all about recreating that origins of death metal sound, so in that respect, they have done a great job.\" writes Soul Killer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soulkillerwebzine.com/reviews/r.htm#REVULSED|title=Revulsed - ''Infernal Atrocity''|publisher=Soul Killer|accessdate=October 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{track listing\n| all_writing = \n| title1 = Rapacious Engorgement\n| length1 = 3:57\n| title2 = Agonizing Putrid Self-Infliction\n| length2 = 3:50\n| title3 = Pestilential Articulation\n| length3 = 3:39\n| title4 = Imposed Cognitive Reconstruction\n| length4 = 4:00\n| title5 = Transmutational Crainiotomy\n| length5 = 3:54\n| title6 = Archetypal Cauterization\n| length6 = 4:13\n| title7 = Enticement to Carnivorous Impoverishment\n| length7 = 4:04\n| title8 = Celestial Perspicacity\