rth, Steven E.]] ''Six Armies in Tennessee: The Chickamauga and Chattanooga Campaigns''. Lincoln: University of Nebraska Press, 1998. {{ISBN|0-8032-9813-7}}.\n* [http://www.nps.gov/hps/abpp/battles/tn017.htm National Park Service battle description]\n* [http://www.nps.gov/hps/abpp/CWSII/TennesseeBattlefieldProfiles/Hartsville%20to%20Johnsonville.pdf CWSAC report update]\n\n==Primary sources==\n* U.S. War Department, [http://ebooks.library.cornell.edu/m/moawar/waro.html ''The War of the Rebellion'']: ''a Compilation of the [[Official Records of the American Civil War|Official Records]] of the Union and Confederate Armies''. Washington, DC: U.S. Government Printing Office, 1880&ndash;1901.\n*[https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=coo.31924077699720;view=1up;seq=427 '''Tullahoma Campaign Union order of battle, organization and strength''' (''Official Records, Series I, Volume XXIII, Part 1, pages 411-424'')]\n*[https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=coo.31924077699720;view=1up;seq=601 '''Tullahoma Campaign Confederate organization and strength''' (''Official Records, Series I, Volume XXIII, Part 1, pages 585-586'')]\n\n\n[[Category:Lightning Brigade| ]]\n[[Category:Union Army brigades]]\n[[Category:Illinois in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:Indiana in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:Mounted Infantry in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1863]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations disestablished in 1864]]\n", "name_user": "Hhfjbaker", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lightning_Brigade_(US_Army_of_the_Cumberland_1863)"}
{"title_page": "Digambara", "text_new": "[[File:Acharya Vishuddh Sagar ji maharaj.jpg|thumb|Acharya Vishuddh Sagar ji maharaj]]\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=December 2015}}\n[[File:Acharya KundaKunda.jpg|thumb|Image depicting Acharya [[Kundakunda]] ]]\n{{Jainism}}\n'''''Digambara''''' ({{IPAc-en|d|\u026a|\u02c8|g|\u028c|m|b|\u0259r|\u0259}}; \"sky-clad\") is one of the two major [[Jain schools and branches|schools of Jainism]], the other being ''[[\u015av\u0113t\u0101mbara]]'' (white-clad). The word ''Digambara'' ([[Sanskrit]]) means \"sky-clad\", refers to their traditional monastic practice of neither possessing nor wearing any clothes.<ref name=\"Long2013p17\">{{cite book|author=Jeffery D Long |title=Jainism: An Introduction|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=I3gAAwAAQBAJ |year=2013|publisher=I.B.Tauris|isbn=978-0-85771-392-6 |pages=17\u201318}}</ref>\n\nThe Digambara and Svetambara traditions have had historical differences ranging from their dress code, their temples and iconography, attitude towards Jain nuns, their legends and the texts they consider as important.<ref name=\"Dundas2002\">{{cite book|author=Paul Dundas|title=The Jains|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jt6-YXE2aUwC |year=2002|publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-0-415-26606-2|pages=53\u201359, 64\u201380, 286\u2013287 with footnotes 21 and 32}}</ref><ref name=\"Wiley2009\">{{cite book|author=Kristi L. Wiley|title=The A to Z of Jainism|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kUz9o-EKTpwC |year=2009|publisher=Scarecrow|isbn=978-0-8108-6821-2|pages=83\u201384}}</ref><ref name=\"JainFischer1978\">{{cite book|author1=Jyotindra Jain|author2=Eberhard Fischer|title=Jaina Iconography|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gFZ7vQ2jwlEC |year=1978|publisher=BRILL Academic|isbn=90-04-05259-3|pages=1\u20132, 8\u20139, xxxiv\u2013xxxv}}</ref> [[Digambara monk]]s cherish the virtue of non-attachment and non-possession of any material goods. They do not have clothes, nor own a begging bowl. They traditionally live and travel naked, and receive donated food with open palms. The monks carry a ''picchi'' (community owned), which is a broom made up of fallen peacock feathers for removing and thus saving the life of insects in their path or before they sit.<ref name=\"Long2013p17\"/> The Digambara literature can be traced only to the 1st-millennium CE, with its oldest surviving sacred text being the mid 2nd-century ''Satkhandagama'' of Dharasena (Mudbidri manuscripts).<ref>{{cite book|author=Paul Dundas|title=The Jains|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=jdjNkZoGFCgC |year=2002| publisher=Routledge |isbn= 978-0-415-26605-5|pages=63\u201365}}</ref> One of the most important scholar-monks of the ''Digambara'' tradition was [[Kundakunda]]. \n\nDigambara Jain communities are currently found mainly in basadis (basti) of [[Karnataka]], parts of south [[Maharashtra]] and [[Madhya Pradesh]].<ref name=\"Long2013p60\">{{cite book|author=Jeffery D Long|title=Jainism: An Introduction|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=I3gAAwAAQBAJ |year=2013|publisher=I.B.Tauris|isbn=978-0-85771-392-6|pages=60\u201361}}</ref><ref name=\"JainFischer1978\"/> According to [[Jeffery D. Long]] \u2013 a scholar of Hindu and Jain studies, less than one fifth of all Jains in India have a Digambara heritage.<ref name=\"Long2013p20\">{{cite book|author=Jeffery D Long |title=Jainism: An Introduction|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=I3gAAwAAQBAJ |year=2013|publisher= I.B.Tauris|isbn=978-0-85771-392-6 |page=20}}</ref>\n\n==Nomenclature==\nAccording to Zimmer, the word ''Digambara'' is a combination of two [[Sanskrit Language|Sanskrit]] words: ''dik'' (\u0926\u093f\u0915\u094d) (space, sky) and ''ambara'' (\u0905\u092e\u094d\u092c\u0930) (garment), referring to those whose garments are of the element that fills the four quarters of space.{{sfn|Zimmer|1953|p=210}}\n\n==History==\nIn 1943, [[Heinrich Zimmer]] proposed that the Greek records of 4th-century BC mention [[gymnosophists]] (naked philosophers) which may have links to the tradition of \"nude ascetics\" claimed by the ''Digambaras''.{{sfn|Zimmer|1953|p=210}} In 2011, [[Patrick Olivelle]] stated that the context in which the Greek records mention gymnosophists include ritual suicide by cremation traceable to ancient [[Brahmanism]], rather than the traditional Jain ritual of suicide by starvation (''sallekhana'').<ref name=\"Olivelle2011p207\">{{cite book|author=Patrick Olivelle|title=Ascetics and Brahmins: Studies in Ideologies and Institutions|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=TecNS3Vi2F4C&pg=PA207 |year=2011|publisher=Anthem Press|isbn= 978-0-85728-432-7 |pages=207\u2013208 with footnotes }}</ref>\n\nDundas talks about the archeological evidences which indicate that Jain monks moved from the practice of total nudity towards wearing clothes in later period. Tirthankara statues found in Mathura and dated to 2nd-century CE or after are naked.<ref name=\"Dundas2002p113\">{{cite book|author=Paul Dundas|title=The Jains|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jdjNkZoGFCgC |year=2002|publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-0-415-26605-5|pages=113\u2013115}}</ref> The oldest Tirthankara statue wearing a cloth is dated in 5th century CE.{{sfn|Upinder Singh|2016|p=444}} ''Digamabara'' statues of tirthankara belonging to Gupta period has half-closed eyes.{{sfn|Umakant Premanand Shah|1987|p=4}}\n\nThe Digambaras and Svetambaras disagree on how the Digambara subtradition started in Jainism.{{sfn|Dundas|2002|pp=46\u201348}} According to Digambaras, they are the original followers of Mahavira and Svetambaras branched off later in the time of Bhadrabahu when their forecasted twelve-year famine triggered their migration from central India.{{sfn|Dundas|2002|pp=46\u201348}} One group of Jain monks headed west and north towards Rajasthan, while the second group headed south towards Karnataka. The former became Svetambaras and retained their \"heretic\" beliefs and practices such as wearing \"white clothes\" they adopted there, say the Digambaras.{{sfn|Dundas|2002|pp=46\u201348}} In contrast, according to Svetambaras, they are the original followers, and Digambaras arose 609 years after the death of Mahavira (about 1st-century CE) because of an arrogant man named Sivabhuti who became a Jain monk in a fit of pique after a fight at home.{{sfn|Dundas|2002|pp=46\u201348}} He is accused of starting the Digambara Jain tradition with what Svetambara call as \"eight concealments\", of rejecting Jain texts preserved by the Svetambara tradition, and misunderstanding the Jain ideology including those related to nuns and clothes.{{sfn|Dundas|2002|pp=46\u201348}} Neither of these explanations can be found in early Jain or non-Jain texts. The earliest version of this Digambara story appears in the 10th-century CE, while the earliest version of the Svetambara story appears in the 5th-century CE.{{sfn|Dundas|2002|pp=47\u201348}}\n\n=== Lineage ===\n{{See also|Pattavali}}\n[[File:Djtradition marhiaji.jpg|thumb|Stela at Marhiaji, [[Jabalpur]], showing the transmission of the oral tradition, erected on the 2500th anniversary of Lord Mahavira's ''nirvana'']]\nAccording to ''Digambara'' texts, after liberation of the Lord [[Mahavira]], three ''Anubaddha Keval\u012bs'' attained ''[[Kevala Jnana|Kevalaj\u00f1\u0101na]]'' (omniscience) sequentially \u2013 [[Indrabhuti Gautama|Gautama]] ''[[Ganadhara|Ga\u0146adhara]]'', ''Acharya'' [[Sudharma]], and [[Jambusvami]] in next 62 years.{{sfn|Vijay K. Jain|2012|p=xi-xii}} During the next hundred years, five ''\u0100ch\u0101ryas'' had complete knowledge of the scriptures, as such, called ''\u015aruta Keval\u012bs'', the last of them being ''\u0100ch\u0101rya'' Bhadrabahu.{{sfn|Pereira|1977|p=5}}{{sfn|Vijay K. Jain|2012|p=xii}} Spiritual lineage of heads of monastic orders is known as ''[[Pattavali]]''.{{sfn|Cort|2010|p=335}} Digambara tradition consider [[Dharasena]] to be the 33rd teacher in succession of Gautama, 683 years after the ''[[Moksha (Jainism)|nirvana]]'' of Mahavira.{{sfn|Dundas|2002|p=79}}\n\nIn the Digambara tradition, the following lineage of teachers are revered: [[Mahavira]], [[Indrabhuti Gautama|Gautama]], [[Kundakunda]],<ref>Jaini, Padmanabh (1991), Gender and Salvation: Jaina Debates on the Spiritual Liberation of Women, University of California Press, pages 31\u201332</ref> [[Bhadrabahu]], [[Umaswati|Umaswami]], [[Samantabhadra (Jain monk)|Samantabhadra]], [[Siddhasena Divakara]],[[Pujyapada]], [[Manatunga]], [[Virasena]],<ref>Satkhandagama : Dhaval (Jivasthana) Satparupana-I (Enunciation of Existence-I) An English Translation of Part 1 of the Dhavala Commentary on the Satkhandagama of Acarya Pushpadanta & Bhutabali Dhavala commentary by Acarya Virasena English tr. by Prof. Nandlal Jain, Ed. by Prof. Ashok Jain {{ISBN|978-81-86957-47-9}}</ref> [[Jinasena]], [[Nemichandra]].{{cn|date=November 2019}}\n\nKundakunda is considered the most significant scholar monk of the Digambara tradition of Jainism. He authored [[Prakrit]] texts such as the ''[[Samayas\u0101ra]]'' and the ''[[Pravacanas\u0101ra]]''. Other prominent ''[[Acharya]]s'' of this tradition were, [[Virasena]] (author of a commentary on the ''[[Dhavala]]''), [[Samantabhadra (Jain monk)|Samantabhadra]] and [[Siddhasena Divakara]]. The ''[[Satkhandagama]]'' and ''[[Kasayapahuda]]'' have major significance in the ''Digambara'' tradition.\n\n==Scripture and literature==\nThe ''Digambara'' sect of Jainism rejects the texts and canonical literature of the ''[[Svetambara]]'' sect.{{sfn|Dundas|2002|pp=79\u201380}}{{sfn|Upinder Singh|2009|p=444}} They believe that the words of Mahavira neither survive nor could be recorded. The original teachings went through a rapid period of decline, state the Digambaras, and Svetambara claims of preserving the sacred knowledge and ancient ''angas'' is false.{{sfn|Dundas|2002|pp=79\u201380}}\n\nAccording to the ''Digambaras'', their 33rd ''ach\u0101rya'' was [[Dharasena]] who knew one ''anga'', and he taught these to [[Pushpadanta (Jain monk)|Pushpadanta]] and [[Bhutabali]], 683 years after the ''[[Moksha (Jainism)|moksha]]'' of Mahavira.{{sfn|Dundas|2002|p=79}} That ''anga'' was also lost with the death of those two. Dharasena's teachings that have survived are ''[[Shatkhandagama|\u1e62a\u1e6dkha\u1e45\u1e0d\u0101gama]]'' (Scripture of Six Parts) and ''Kasayapahuda'' (Treatise on the Passions), which were written on palm leaves near a cave in Mount Girnar (Gujarat) and a copy of which with a 12th-century commentary came to Tulu Nadu (south Karnataka).{{sfn|Dundas|2002|pp=63\u201365, 79\u201380}} This has survived as the Mudbidri manuscripts, which were used by regional Jains not for reading and study, but as an object of devotional worship for centuries.{{sfn|Dundas|2002|pp=63\u201365, 79\u201380}} In the 19th century, the fragile and decaying manuscript was copied and portions of it leaked to scholars between 1896 and 1922 despite objections of Digambara monks. It is considered to be the oldest known ''Digambara'' text ultimately traceable to the 2nd-century CE.{{sfn|Dundas|2002|pp=63\u201365, 79\u201380}} \n\nThese two oldest known Digambara tradition texts \u2013 ''Satkhandagama'' and ''Kasayapahuda'' \u2013 are predominantly a treatise about the soul and [[Karma]] theory, written in Prakrit language. Philologically, the text belongs to about the 2nd-century, and has nothing that suggests it is of \"immemorial antiquity\".{{sfn|Dundas|2002|pp=63\u201365, 79\u201380}} In details, the text is quite similar in its teachings to those found in ''Prajnapana'' \u2013 the 4th ''upanga'' \u2013 of Svetambaras.{{sfn|Dundas|2002|pp=79\u201380}} Between the two, the poetic meter of ''Satkhandagama'' suggests it was composed after the Svetambara text.{{sfn|Dundas|2002|pp=79\u201380}}\n\nDigambaras, unlike Svetambaras, do not have a canon. They do have a quasi-canonical literature grouped into four literary categories called ''anuyoga'' (exposition) since the time of the Digambara scholar Rakshita.{{sfn|Dundas|2002|p=80}} The ''prathmanuyoga'' (first exposition) contains the universal history, the ''karananuyoga'' (calculation exposition) contains works on cosmology, the ''charananuyoga'' (behaviour exposition) includes texts about proper behaviour for monks and lay people, while the ''dravyanuyoga'' (entity exposition) contains metaphysical discussions.{{sfn|Dundas|2002|p=80}} In the Digambara tradition, it is not the oldest texts that have survived in its temples and monasteries that attract the most study or reverence, rather it is the late 9th-century ''Mahapurana'' (universal history) of Jinasena that is the most revered and cherished.{{sfn|Dundas|2002|pp=80-81}} The ''Mahapurana'' includes not only religious history, but also the mythical sociological history of the Jaina people \u2013 including the Jain caste system and its origins as formulated by [[Rishabhanatha]] \u2013 from the Digambara Jaina perspective.{{sfn|Jaini|2000|pp=32, 229\u2013239}}\n\nThe ''Digamabara'' tradition maintains a long list of revered teachers, and this list includes Kundakunda, Samantabhadra, Pujyapada, Jinasena, Akalanka, Vidyanandi, Somadeva and Asadhara.{{sfn|Jaini|2000|p=28}}\n\n==Practices==\n===Monasticism===\n{{Main|Digambara monk}}\nThe lifestyle and behavioral conduct of a ''Digambara'' monk is guided by a code called ''mulacara'' (''mulachara''). This includes 28 ''m\u016bla gu\u0146as'' (primary attributes) for the monk.{{sfn|Pramansagar|2008|p=189\u2013191}} The oldest text containing these norms is the 2nd-century ''[[Mulachara]]'' attributed to Vattekara, that probably originated in the Mathura region.{{sfn|Dundas|2002|p=80}} \n\nThese are: 5 ''mah\u0101vratas'' (great vows); 5 ''samitis'' (restraints); 5 ''indriya nirodha'' (control of the five senses); 6 ''\u0101va\u015byakas'' (essential observations); and 7 ''niyamas'' (rules).{{sfn|Vijay K. Jain|2013|pp=189\u2013191, 196\u2013197}}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! No.\n! ''Guna''<br>(attribute)\n! Remarks\n|- style=\"background:#ffedcd;\"\n|rowspan=\"5\"|''Mahavratas''-<br /> Five Great Vows{{sfn|Vijay K. Jain|2011|p=93\u2013100}}{{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1926|p=26}}\n|1. ''[[Ahimsa in Jainism|Ahimsa]]''\n|neither injure, nor ask, nor encourage another to injure any living being through actions, words or thoughts. This includes injury caused by cooking, starting a fire to cook, plucking a fruit, or any conduct that harms living beings{{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1926|pp=27\u201328}}\n|- style=\"background:#ffedcd;\"\n|2. [[Satya]]\n| To speak the truth, to remain silent if his speaking the truth will lead to injury to living beings{{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1926|p=29}}\n|- style=\"background:#ffedcd;\" \n|3. ''[[Asteya]]''\n| Not to take anything unless given, and not accepting anything more than what is necessary and needed{{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1926|p=30}}\n|- style=\"background:#ffedcd;\"\n|4. ''[[Brahmacharya]]''\n|No sex, no natural or unnatural sexual gratification through action (viewing, participating, encouraging), words (hearing, reciting, reading, writing), or thoughts{{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1926|pp=30\u201331}}\n|- style=\"background:#ffedcd;\"\n|5. ''[[Aparigraha]]''\n|Renunciation of all worldly things, property, want, and all possessions external to soul{{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1926|pp=31\u201332}}\n|- style=\"background:#ffe4b3;\"\n|rowspan=\"5\"|''Samiti''-<br /> Regulations{{sfn|Vijay K. Jain|2012|p=144\u2013145}}{{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1926|pp=32\u201338}}\n|6. ''irya''\n|Walk carefully on much trodden paths, after viewing land to the extent of four cubits (2 yards). Do not walk in the dark or on the grass to avoid accidental injury to other living beings.{{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1926|p=33}} He should not run to save himself if charged by a wild animal or if a violent person is about to injure him, as running can cause injury to other living beings.{{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1926|p=33}}\n|- style=\"background:#ffe4b3;\"\n|7. ''bhasha''\n| Avoid slander, back-biting, false speech. He must avoid intentionally long or short statements that mislead or help create misunderstanding, doubts, misinformation, hypocrisy, bad blood or conceit in his audience.{{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1926|pp=34\u201335}}\n|- style=\"background:#ffe4b3;\"\n|8. ''esana''\n|To never accept objectionable food nor eat more palatable items from those received.{{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1926|pp=35\u201336}}\n|- style=\"background:#ffe4b3;\"\n|9. ''adana-nikshepana''\n|Carefulness in the handling the ''pichchi'' (feather bundle to remove insects in his path) and ''kamandalu'' (hollow vegetable gourd to filter water)\n|- style=\"background:#ffe4b3;\"\n|10. ''pratish\u1e6dapan''\n|To excrete body waste after carefully brushing aside insects and other living beings.{{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1926|pp=37\u201338}}\n|- style=\"background:#faba00;\" \n|rowspan=\"1\"|''Indrinirodh''{{sfn|Vijay K. Jain|2013|pp=189\u2013191, 196\u2013197}}\n|11\u201315. Control of the five senses\n|Shedding all attachment and aversion towards the sense objects pertaining to touch (''spar\u015bana''), taste (''rasana''), smell (''ghr\u0101\u1e47a''), sight (''cak\u015bu''), and hearing (''\u015brotra''). The ''sadhu'' (monk) must eradicate all desires and activities that please the mind through his senses.{{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1926|pp=38\u201339}} He must end all ties, relationships and entanglements with his family and friends before he renounced.{{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1926|pp=38\u201339}}\n|- style=\"background:#ffd280;\"\n|rowspan=\"6\"|''Avasyakas'' \u2013<br>Essential observations{{sfn|Vijay K. Jain|2012|p=143}}{{sfn|Vijay K. Jain|2013|pp=189\u2013191, 196\u2013197}}\n|16. ''[[S\u0101m\u0101yika]]''\n|Practice equanimous dispassion towards everything for eighteen ''ghari'' a day (1 ''ghari'' = about 24 minutes){{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1926|pp=38\u201339}} This \n|- style=\"background:#ffd280;\" \n|17. ''stuti''\n|Salute the divine (''[[Tirthankaras]]'')\n|- style=\"background:#ffd280;\" \n|18. ''vandana''\n|Medidate upon and adore ''acharyas'', ''gurus'', idols and images of gods{{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1926|pp=26, 38\u201339}}<ref name=\"CaillatBalbir2008p236\">{{cite book|author1= Colette Caillat|author2= Nalini Balbir|title=Jaina Studies |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=ecKCrO6nLiAC |year=2008|publisher= Motilal Banarsidass |isbn=978-81-208-3247-3|pages=236\u2013241 with footnotes }}</ref><ref name=\"Wiley2009p226\">{{cite book|author=Kristi L. Wiley|title=The A to Z of Jainism |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=cIhCCwAAQBAJ |year=2009 |publisher=Scarecrow |isbn= 978-0-8108-6337-8|pages=226\u2013227}}</ref>\n|- style=\"background:#ffd280;\"\n|19. ''[[Pratikramana]]''\n| Confession, repentance and self-censure for having violated any vows and rules of conduct;<ref name=\"Wiley2009p170\">{{cite book|author=Kristi L. Wiley|title=The A to Z of Jainism |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cIhCCwAAQBAJ |year=2009|publisher=Scarecrow |isbn=978-0-8108-6337-8|page=170}}</ref> dissociate one's soul from any virtuous or evil ''karmas'', in the current or past lives.\n|- style=\"background:#ffd280;\" \n|20. ''Pratikhayan''\n|Recite mantra that lists and promises future renunciation of food, drink and comforts and to forfend future faults<ref name=\"Williams1991p184\">{{cite book|author=Robert Williams|title=Jaina Yoga: A Survey of the Mediaeval \u015ar\u0101vak\u0101c\u0101ras |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=LLKcrIJ6oscC&pg=PA184 |year=1991|publisher= Motilal Banarsidass|isbn =978-81-208-0775-4 |pages=184 }}</ref>\n|- style=\"background:#ffd280;\" \n|21. ''[[Kayotsarga]]''\n|Giving up attachment to the body for a limited period of time.<ref name=\"Williams1991p184\"/> Typically, this is a standing naked and motionless posture of a form common in [[Bahubali]] iconography.<ref>{{cite book|author=Umakant Premanand Shah|title=Jaina-r\u016bpa-ma\u1e47\u1e0dana|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=m_y_P4duSXsC&pg=PA79 |year=1987|publisher=Abhinav Publications|isbn=978-81-7017-208-6|pages=79\u201380 }}</ref>\n|- style=\"background:#ffdb9a;\" \n|rowspan=\"7\"|''Niyama''-<br /> Rules{{sfn|Vijay K. Jain|2013|pp=189\u2013191, 196\u2013197}}{{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1926|p=46\u201347}}\n|22. ''adantdhavan''\n|Never clean teeth{{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1926|p=47\u201348}}\n|- style=\"background:#ffdb9a;\"\n|23. ''bhushayan''\n|Sleep on hard ground\n|- style=\"background:#ffdb9a;\"\n|24. ''asn\u0101na''\n|Never bathe{{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1926|p=46\u201347}}\n|- style=\"background:#ffdb9a;\"\n|25. ''stithi-bhojan''\n|Eat food in standing posture, accept food in open palms (no utensils){{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1926|p=47\u201348}}\n|- style=\"background:#ffdb9a;\"\n|26. ''{{lang|sa-Latn|ahara}}''\n|Eat food once a day,{{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1926|p=48\u201349}} drink water only when eating meal{{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1926|p=36}}\n|- style=\"background:#ffdb9a;\"\n|27. ''ke\u015ba-lonch''\n|To periodically pluck all hair on his body by his own hand.{{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1926|p=44\u201345}}\n|- style=\"background:#ffdb9a;\"\n|28. nudity\n|Remain completely nude all the time (''digambara''){{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1926|p=45\u201346}}\n|- style=\"background:#ffdb9a;\"\n|}\n\n''Digambara'' monks do not wear any clothes as it is considered to be ''parigraha'' (possession), which ultimately leads to attachment.{{sfn|Dundas|2002|p=45}} The monks carry ''picchi'', a broom made up of fallen peacock feathers for removing small insects to avoid causing injury and ''Kamandalu'' (the gourd for carrying pure, sterilized water).{{sfn|Upinder Singh|2009|p=316}}{{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1926|p=36}} The head of all monastics is called ''[[Acharya|\u0100ch\u0101rya]]'', while the saintly preceptor of saints is the ''up\u0101dhy\u0101ya''.{{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1926|p=21}} The ''\u0100ch\u0101rya'' has 36 primary attributes (''m\u016bla gu\u0146a'') in addition to the 28 mentioned above.{{sfn|Vijay K. Jain|2013|pp=189\u2013191, 196\u2013197}} \n\nThe monks perform ''kayotsarga'' daily, in a rigid and immobile posture, with the arms held stiffly down, knees straight, and toes directed forward.{{sfn|Zimmer|1953|p=210}}\n\n===Nuns===\nFemale monastics in Digambara tradition are known as ''[[aryika]]s''.{{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1926|p=141}} Digambara nuns, unlike the monks in their tradition, wear clothes. Given their beliefs such as non-attachment and non-possession, the Digambara tradition has held that women cannot achieve salvation (moksha) as men can, and the best a nun can achieve is to be reborn as a man in the next rebirth.<ref name=\"Long2013p17\"/> The monks are held to be of higher status than nuns in Digambara monasteries, states Jeffery Long.<ref name=\"Long2013p17\"/> From the Digambara monk's perspective, both Digambara nuns and Svetambara monastic community are simply more pious Jain layperson, who do not or are unable to fully practice the Jain monastic vows.{{sfn|Dundas|2002|pp=49-50}}\n\nDigambara nuns are relatively rare in comparison to the nuns found in Svetambara traditions. According to a 1970s and 1980s survey of Jain subtraditions, there were about 125 Digambara monks in India and 50 Digambara nuns.<ref name=\"Howard2019pt105\">{{cite book|author=Veena R. Howard |title=The Bloomsbury Research Handbook of Indian Philosophy and Gender|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=J1OqDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT105 |year=2019|publisher=Bloomsbury Academic |isbn=978-1-4742-6959-9 |pages=105\u2013106}}</ref> This compared to 3,400 nuns and 1,200 monks in the Svetambara tradition.<ref name=\"Howard2019pt105\"/>\n\n===Digambar akhara===\n{{anchor | Digambar akhara}}\n\nThe '''Digambar Akhara''', which along with other [[akhara]]s, also participates in various inter-sectarian (''[[sampradaya]]'') religious activities  including [[Kumbh Mela]]s, is completely unrelated to Digambar Jain tradition, even though they also practice nudity.<ref name=relDis1>[South Asian Religions on Display: Religious Processions in South Asia and in the Diaspora, Knut A. Jacobsen, ISBN hardback 978-0-415-4373-3, ISBN ebook ISBN hardback 978-0-203-93059-5]</ref>\n\n===Worship===\n[[File:7th - 12th century Mahavira flanked by 24 Tirthankaras in Cave 4, Badami Jain cave temple Karnataka.jpg|thumb|Adinatha image (Badami caves)]]\nThe ''Digambara'' Jains worship completely nude idols of ''tirthankaras'' (omniscient beings) and ''[[siddha]]'' (liberated souls). The ''tirthankara'' is represented either seated in yoga posture or standing in the ''Kayotsarga'' posture.{{sfn|Zimmer|1953|p=209\u2013210}} \n{{quote|The truly \"sky-clad\" (''digambara'') Jaina statue expresses the perfect isolation of the one who has stripped off every bond. His is an absolute \"abiding in itself,\" a strange but perfect aloofness, a nudity of chilling majesty, in its stony simplicity, rigid contours, and abstraction.{{sfn|Zimmer|1953|p=213}}|[[Heinrich Zimmer]]}}\n\n==== Statues ====\n<gallery>\nKizhavalavu (Kilavalavu) -Jain Sculptures.JPG|Kizhavalavu ([[Keelavalavu]]) Sculptures\nGommateshvara Bahubali.jpg|The {{convert|57|ft|m}} high [[Gommateshwara statue]], [[Shravanabelagola]]\nJain statues, Gwalior.jpg|''Tirthankara'' statues at [[Siddhachal Caves]] inside [[Gwalior Fort]], [[Madhya Pradesh]]\nJain statue of Parshvanath, Naugaza temple, Alwar district, Rajasthan, India.jpg|''Tirthankara'' [[Parshvanatha]] statue, [[Rajasthan]]\n</gallery>\n\n==Monastic lineages==\nThere have been several Digambara monastic lineages that all trace their descent to Lord Mahavira. The historical linages included ''[[Mula Sangha]]'' (further vivided into  ''Nandi'', ''Sena'', ''Simha'' and ''Deva'' Sanghas) and now largely extinct [[Kashtha Sangha]] (which included ''Mathura'' sangha, \"\"Lat-Vagad\" etc.), Dravida Sangh.   {{sfn|Carrithers|Humphrey|1991|p=170}} The text Darshana-Sara of Devasena <ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=dXVOXRrYQiQC&pg=PA433&lpg=PA433&dq=darshan+sar+jain+book&source=bl&ots=-lHX9hgrTj&sig=ACfU3U03FFsSGhE4iygTZmTOkrxi1RoxNg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj-qLv67qHkAhVWvZ4KHbkvBcEQ6AEwEHoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=darshan%20sar%20jain%20book&f=false Agama Aura Tripitaka: Eka Anusilana, Volume 2 of \u0100gama Aura Tripi\u1e6daka, Eka Anu\u015bilana, Nagraj (Muni.), Concept Publishing Company, 1986, p. 433]</ref> discusses the supposed differences among the orders. The ''Mula sangha'' orders include ''Deshiya Gana'' (Bhattarakas of Shravanabelgola etc.) and ''[[Balatkara Gana]]'' (Bhattarakas of [[Humcha]], and numerous linages of North/Central India) traditions.<ref>Vidaydgar Johrapurkar, Bha\u1e6d\u1e6d\u0101raka Sampradaya, Solapur, 1958</ref> The ''[[Bhattaraka]]s'' of [[Shravanabelagola]] and [[Mudbidri]] belong to ''Deshiya Gana'' and the ''Bhattaraka'' of [[Humbaj]] belongs to the ''Balatkara Gana''.{{sfn|Sangave|1980|p=299}}\n\nThe extinct [[Yapaniya]] order used nudity like the Digambara orders, but followed some Shvetambara tenets.\n\n==Sub-sects==\n[[File:Acharya5.jpg|thumb|''[[Acharya]]'' [[Vidyasagar (Jain monk)|Vidyasagar]], a prominent [[Digambara monk]]]]\n{{Jain Digambara sects}}\n\nModern ''Digambara'' community is divided into various sub-sects viz. ''[[Digambara Terapanth|Terapanthi]]'', ''[[Bispanthi]]'', ''[[Taran Panth|Taranpanthi]]'' (or ''Samayiapanthi''), ''Gumanapanthi'' and ''Totapanthi''.{{sfn|Sangave|1980|pp=51-56}}\n\nDigambara community was divided into ''Terapanthi'' and ''Bisapanthi'' on the acceptance of authority of ''Bhattaraka''.{{sfn|Long|2008|p=39}}{{Citation not found}}\n\nThe  Bispanth-Terapanth division among the Digambaras emerged in the 17th century in the Jaipur region: [[Sanganer]], [[Amer, India|Amer]] and [[Jaipur]] itself.<ref>John E. Cort \"A Tale of Two Cities: On the Origins of Digambara Sectarianism in North India.\" L. A. Babb, V. Joshi, and M. W. Meister (eds.), Multiple Histories: Culture and Society in the Study of Rajasthan, 39-83. Jaipur: Rawat, 2002.</ref>\n\n===''Terapanthi''===\n{{Main|Digambara Terapanth}}\n[[File:Acharya Gyansagar.jpg|thumb|Acharya [[Gyansagar (Chani)|Gyansagar]]]]\nThe ''Terapanthis'' worship what the idols represent, with ''ashta-dravya'' similarly to the Bispanthis, but replace flowers and fruits with dry substitutes.  The ashta-dravya ''jal'' (water), ''chandan'' (sandal), ''akshata'' (sacred rice), ''pushp'' (yellow rice), ''deep'' (yellow dry coconut), ''dhup'' (''kapoor'' or cloves) and ''phal'' (almonds).{{sfn|Sangave|1980|p=52}} Terapanthi is a reformist sect of ''Digambara'' Jainism that distinguished itself from the ''[[Bispanthi]]'' sect. It formed out of strong opposition to the religious domination of traditional religious leaders called ''[[bhattaraka]]s'' in the 17th century.  They oppose the worship of various minor gods and goddesses. Some ''Terapanthi'' practices, like not using flowers in worship, are followed by most of [[North India]]n Jains. ''Terapanthis'' occur in large numbers in [[Rajasthan]], [[Uttar Pradesh]] and [[Madhya Pradesh]].{{sfn|Sangave|1980|p=52}}\n\nThe Terapanthi movement was born out of the ''Adhyatma'' movement that arose in 1626 AD ([[Vikram Samvat|V.S.]] 1683) in [[Agra]]. Its leading proponent was [[Banarasidas]] of Agra.<ref>Ardhakathanaka: Half a tale, a Study in the Interrelationship between Autobiography and History, Mukunda Lath (trans. and ed.), Jaipur 2005. {{ISBN|978-8129105660}}</ref>{{better source|date=March 2018}}\n\n===''Bispanthi''===\n{{Main|Bispanthi}}\nBesides ''tirthankaras'', ''Bispanthi'' also worship ''[[Yaksha]]'' and ''[[Yakshini]]'' like [[Bhairava]] and [[Kshetrapala]]. Their religious practices include ''[[aarti]]'' and offerings of flowers, fruits and ''[[prasad]]''. ''Bhattarakas'' are their ''dharma-gurus'' and they are concentrated in Rajasthan, [[Gujarat]], Maharastra and South India. {{sfn|Sangave|1980|p=52}}\n\n== Differences with \u015av\u0113t\u0101mbara sect ==\nAccording to ''Digambara'' texts, after attaining ''[[Kevala Jnana]]'' (omniscience), ''[[Arihant (Jainism)|arihant]]'' (omniscient beings) are free from human needs like hunger, thirst, and sleep.{{sfn|Upinder Singh|2009|p=314}} In contrast, \u015av\u0113t\u0101mbara texts preach that it is not so. According to the ''Digambara'' tradition, a soul can attain ''moksha'' (liberation) only from the male body with complete nudity being a necessity.{{sfn|Upinder Singh|2009|p=319}} While, \u015av\u0113t\u0101mbaras believe that women can attain liberation from female body itself and renunciation of clothes is not at all necessary.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Religion}}\n*[[Nudity in religion]]\n*[[God in Jainism]]\n*[[Kshullak]]\n*[[Jain philosophy]]\n*[[Timeline of Jainism]]\n*[[Digambar Jain Mahasabha]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|20em}}\n\n===Sources===\n* {{citation |editor-last=Carrithers |editor-first=Michael |editor-link=Michael Carrithers |editor-last2=Humphrey |editor-first2=Caroline |editor-link2=Caroline Humphrey |title=The Assembly of Listeners: Jains in Society |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LW8czr_HzzwC |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |date=1991 |isbn=0-521-365-05-8 }}\n* {{citation |title=\u0100c\u0101rya Nemichandra's Dravyasa\u1e43graha |isbn=978-81-903639-5-2 |last=Jain |first=Vijay K. |date=2013 |quote={{PD-notice}} |publisher=Vikalp Printers |ref={{sfnref|Vijay K. Jain|2013}} }}\n* {{citation |last=Jain |first=Vijay K. |title=Acharya Amritchandra's Purushartha Siddhyupaya |year=2012 |publisher=Vikalp Printers |isbn=978-81-903639-4-5 |url=https://books.google.com/books?isbn=8190363948 |quote={{PD-notice}} |ref={{sfnref|Vijay K. Jain|2012}} }}\n*{{citation |last=Jain |first=Vijay K. |title=Acharya Umasvami's Tattv\u0101rths\u016btra |publisher=Vikalp Printers |location=(Uttarakhand) India |isbn=978-81-903639-2-1 |edition=1st |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zLmx9bvtglkC |year=2011 |quote={{PD-notice}} |ref={{sfnref|Vijay K. Jain|2011}} }}\n* {{citation |last=Possehl |first=Gregory L. |authorlink=Gregory L. Possehl |title=The Indus Civilization: A Contemporary Perspective |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pmAuAsi4ePIC |date=2002 |publisher=[[Rowman Altamira]] |isbn=978-0-7591-0172-2 }}\n*{{citation |last=Pramansagar |first=Muni |title=Jain Tattva-Vidya |year=2008 |publisher=Bhartiya Gyanpeeth |location=India |isbn=978-81-263-1480-5 }}\n* {{citation |last=Singh |first=Upinder |authorlink=Upinder Singh |title=A History Of Ancient And Early Medieval India: From The Stone Age To The 12Th Century |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GW5Gx0HSXKUC |year=2009 |publisher=[[Pearson Education]] |isbn=978-81-317-1120-0 |ref={{sfnref|Upinder Singh|2009}} }}\n* {{citation |last=Singh |first=Upinder |authorlink=Upinder Singh |title=A History of Ancient and Early Medieval India: From the Stone Age to the 12th Century |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Pq2iCwAAQBAJ |publisher=[[Pearson Education]] |date=2016 |isbn=978-93-325-6996-6 |ref={{sfnref|Upinder Singh|2016}} }}\n*{{citation |last=Jones |first=Constance |last2=Ryan |first2=James D. |title=Encyclopedia of Hinduism |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OgMmceadQ3gC&pg=PA134 |year=2006 |publisher=Infobase Publishing |isbn=978-0-8160-7564-5 }}\n* {{citation |last=Dundas |first=Paul |authorlink=Paul Dundas |title=The Jains |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=X8iAAgAAQBAJ |edition=Second |date=2002 |orig-year=1992 |publisher=[[Routledge]] |isbn=0-415-26605-X }}\n* {{citation |last=Jaini |first=Padmanabh S. |authorlink=Padmanabh Jaini |title=Gender and Salvation: Jaina Debates on the Spiritual Liberation of Women |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GRA-uoUFz3MC |date=1991 |isbn=0-520-06820-3 |publisher=[[University of California Press]] }}\n* {{citation |last=Jaini |first=Padmanabh S. |authorlink=Padmanabh Jaini |title=Collected Papers On Jaina Studies |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HPggiM7y1aYC |date=2000 |publisher=[[Motilal Banarsidass]] |location=[[Delhi]] |edition=First |isbn=81-208-1691-9 }}\n*{{cite book|first=Jeffery D|last= Long |title=Jainism: An Introduction |year=2008|publisher= I.B.Tauris|isbn=978-0-85771-392-6}}\n* {{citation |last=Pereira |first=Jos\u00e9 |authorlink=Jos\u00e9 Pereira (scholar) |title=Monolithic Jinas |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LMTgiygj4-oC |publisher=[[Motilal Banarsidass]] |date=1977 |isbn=0-8426-1027-8 }}\n* {{citation |last=Mookerji |first=Radha Kumud |authorlink=Radha Kumud Mukherjee |title=Chandragupta Maurya and his times |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=i-y6ZUheQH8C |edition=4th |year=1988 |origyear=first published in 1966 |publisher=[[Motilal Banarsidass]] |isbn=81-208-0433-3 }}\n* {{citation |last=Sangave |first=Vilas Adinath |authorlink=Vilas Adinath Sangave |title=Jaina Community: A Social Survey |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FWdWrRGV_t8C |publisher=Popular Prakashan |date=1980 |orig-year=1959 |isbn=0-317-12346-7 }}\n* {{citation |last=Shah |first=Umakant Premanand |authorlink=Umakant Premanand Shah |title=Jaina-r\u016bpa-ma\u1e47\u1e0dana: Jaina iconography |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=m_y_P4duSXsC |date=1987 |publisher=[[Abhinav Publications]] |isbn=81-7017-208-X |ref={{sfnref|Umakant Premanand Shah|1987}} }}\n* {{citation |last=Cort |first=John |authorlink=John E. Cort |title=Framing the Jina: Narratives of Icons and Idols in Jain History |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MDBpq23-0QoC |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |date=2010 |orig-year=1953 |isbn=978-0-19-538502-1 }}\n* {{citation |last=Zimmer |first=Heinrich |authorlink=Heinrich Zimmer |title=Philosophies Of India |date=1953 |orig-year=April 1952 |editor-first=Joseph |editor-last=Campbell |editorlink=Joseph Campbell |publisher=[[Routledge]] & Kegan Paul Ltd |location=[[London]], E.C. 4 |url=https://archive.org/details/Philosophy.of.India.by.Heinrich.Zimmer |isbn=978-81-208-0739-6 |quote={{PD-notice}} }}\n*{{citation |title=Sannyasa Dharma |date=1926 |first=Champat Rai |last=Jain |authorlink=Champat Rai Jain |url=https://archive.org/details/SannyasaDharma |ref={{sfnref|Champat Rai Jain|1926}} }}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commonscatinline}}\n*[http://www.idjo.org International Digamber Jain Organization]\n\n{{Jainism topics}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Nudity in religion]]\n[[Category:Digambara| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=December 2015}}\n[[File:Acharya KundaKunda.jpg|thumb|Image depicting Acharya [[Kundakunda]] ]]\n{{Jainism}}\n'''''Digambara''''' ({{IPAc-en|d|\u026a|\u02c8|g|\u028c|m|b|\u0259r|\u0259}}; \"sky-clad\") is one of the two major [[Jain schools and branches|schools of Jainism]], the other being ''[[\u015av\u0113t\u0101mbara]]'' (white-clad). The word ''Digambara'' ([[Sanskrit]]) means \"sky-clad\", refers to their traditional monastic practice of neither possessing nor wearing any clothes.<ref name=\"Long2013p17\">{{cite book|author=Jeffery D Long |title=Jainism: An Introduction|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=I3gAAwAAQBAJ |year=2013|publisher=I.B.Tauris|isbn=978-0-85771-392-6 |pages=17\u201318}}</ref>\n\nThe Digambara and Svetambara traditions have had historical differences ranging from their dress code, their temples and iconography, attitude towards Jain nuns, their legends and the texts they consider as important.<ref name=\"Dundas2002\">{{cite book|author=Paul Dundas|title=The Jains|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jt6-YXE2aUwC |year=2002|publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-0-415-26606-2|pages=53\u201359, 64\u201380, 286\u2013287 with footnotes 21 and 32}}</ref><ref name=\"Wiley2009\">{{cite book|author=Kristi L. Wiley|title=The A to Z of Jainism|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kUz9o-EKTpwC |year=2009|publisher=Scarecrow|isbn=978-0-8108-6821-2|pages=83\u201384}}</ref><ref name=\"JainFischer1978\">{{cite book|author1=Jyotindra Jain|author2=Eberhard Fischer|title=Jaina Iconography|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gFZ7vQ2jwlEC |year=1978|publisher=BRILL Academic|isbn=90-04-05259-3|pages=1\u20132, 8\u20139, xxxiv\u2013xxxv}}</ref> [[Digambara monk]]s cherish the virtue of non-attachment and non-possession of any material goods. They do not have clothes, nor own a begging bowl. They traditionally live and travel naked, and receive donated food with open palms. The monks carry a ''picchi'' (community owned), which is a broom made up of fallen peacock feathers for removing and thus saving the life of insects in their path or before they sit.<ref name=\"Long2013p17\"/> The Digambara literature can be traced only to the 1st-millennium CE, with its oldest surviving sacred text being the mid 2nd-century ''Satkhandagama'' of Dharasena (Mudbidri manuscripts).<ref>{{cite book|author=Paul Dundas|title=The Jains|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=jdjNkZoGFCgC |year=2002| publisher=Routledge |isbn= 978-0-415-26605-5|pages=63\u201365}}</ref> One of the most important scholar-monks of the ''Digambara'' tradition was [[Kundakunda]]. \n\nDigambara Jain communities are currently found mainly in basadis (basti) of [[Karnataka]], parts of south [[Maharashtra]] and [[Madhya Pradesh]].<ref name=\"Long2013p60\">{{cite book|author=Jeffery D Long|title=Jainism: An Introduction|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=I3gAAwAAQBAJ |year=2013|publisher=I.B.Tauris|isbn=978-0-85771-392-6|pages=60\u201361}}</ref><ref name=\"JainFischer1978\"/> According to [[Jeffery D. Long]] \u2013 a scholar of Hindu and Jain studies, less than one fifth of all Jains in India have a Digambara heritage.<ref name=\"Long2013p20\">{{cite book|author=Jeffery D Long |title=Jainism: An Introduction|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=I3gAAwAAQBAJ |year=2013|publisher= I.B.Tauris|isbn=978-0-85771-392-6 |page=20}}</ref>\n\n==Nomenclature==\nAccording to Zimmer, the word ''Digambara'' is a combination of two [[Sanskrit Language|Sanskrit]] words: ''dik'' (\u0926\u093f\u0915\u094d) (space, sky) and ''ambara'' (\u0905\u092e\u094d\u092c\u0930) (garment), referring to those whose garments are of the element that fills the four quarters of space.{{sfn|Zimmer|1953|p=210}}\n\n==History==\nIn 1943, [[Heinrich Zimmer]] proposed that the Greek records of 4th-century BC mention [[gymnosophists]] (naked philosophers) which may have links to the tradition of \"nude ascetics\" claimed by the ''Digambaras''.{{sfn|Zimmer|1953|p=210}} In 2011, [[Patrick Olivelle]] stated that the context in which the Greek records mention gymnosophists include ritual suicide by cremation traceable to ancient [[Brahmanism]], rather than the traditional Jain ritual of suicide by starvation (''sallekhana'').<ref name=\"Olivelle2011p207\">{{cite book|author=Patrick Olivelle|title=Ascetics and Brahmins: Studies in Ideologies and Institutions|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=TecNS3Vi2F4C&pg=PA207 |year=2011|publisher=Anthem Press|isbn= 978-0-85728-432-7 |pages=207\u2013208 with footnotes }}</ref>\n\nDundas talks about the archeological evidences which indicate that Jain monks moved from the practice of total nudity towards wearing clothes in later period. Tirthankara statues found in Mathura and dated to 2nd-century CE or after are naked.<ref name=\"Dundas2002p113\">{{cite book|author=Paul Dundas|title=The Jains|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jdjNkZoGFCgC |year=2002|publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-0-415-26605-5|pages=113\u2013115}}</ref> The oldest Tirthankara statue wearing a cloth is dated in 5th century CE.{{sfn|Upinder Singh|2016|p=444}} ''Digamabara'' statues of tirthankara belonging to Gupta period has half-closed eyes.{{sfn|Umakant Premanand Shah|1987|p=4}}\n\nThe Digambaras and Svetambaras disagree on how the Digambara subtradition started in Jainism.{{sfn|Dundas|2002|pp=46\u201348}} According to Digambaras, they are the original followers of Mahavira and Svetambaras branched off later in the time of Bhadrabahu when their forecasted twelve-year famine triggered their migration from central India.{{sfn|Dundas|2002|pp=46\u201348}} One group of Jain monks headed west and north towards Rajasthan, while the second group headed south towards Karnataka. The former became Svetambaras and retained their \"heretic\" beliefs and practices such as wearing \"white clothes\" they adopted there, say the Digambaras.{{sfn|Dundas|2002|pp=46\u201348}} In contrast, according to Svetambaras, they are the original followers, and Digambaras arose 609 years after the death of Mahavira (about 1st-century CE) because of an arrogant man named Sivabhuti who became a Jain monk in a fit of pique after a fight at home.{{sfn|Dundas|2002|pp=46\u201348}} He is accused of starting the Digambara Jain tradition with what Svetambara call as \"eight concealments\", of rejecting Jain texts preserved by the Svetambara tradition, and misunderstanding the Jain ideology including those related to nuns and clothes.{{sfn|Dundas|2002|pp=46\u201348}} Neither of these explanations can be found in early Jain or non-Jain texts. The earliest version of this Digambara story appears in the 10th-century CE, while the earliest version of the Svetambara story appears in the 5th-century CE.{{sfn|Dundas|2002|pp=47\u201348}}\n\n=== Lineage ===\n{{See also|Pattavali}}\n[[File:Djtradition marhiaji.jpg|thumb|Stela at Marhiaji, [[Jabalpur]], showing the transmission of the oral tradition, erected on the 2500th anniversary of Lord Mahavira's ''nirvana'']]\nAccording to ''Digambara'' texts, after liberation of the Lord [[Mahavira]], three ''Anubaddha Keval\u012bs'' attained ''[[Kevala Jnana|Kevalaj\u00f1\u0101na]]'' (omniscience) sequentially \u2013 [[Indrabhuti Gautama|Gautama]] ''[[Ganadhara|Ga\u0146adhara]]'', ''Acharya'' [[Sudharma]], and [[Jambusvami]] in next 62 years.{{sfn|Vijay K. Jain|2012|p=xi-xii}} During the next hundred years, five ''\u0100ch\u0101ryas'' had complete knowledge of the scriptures, as such, called ''\u015aruta Keval\u012bs'', the last of them being ''\u0100ch\u0101rya'' Bhadrabahu.{{sfn|Pereira|1977|p=5}}{{sfn|Vijay K. Jain|2012|p=xii}} Spiritual lineage of heads of monastic orders is known as ''[[Pattavali]]''.{{sfn|Cort|2010|p=335}} Digambara tradition consider [[Dharasena]] to be the 33rd teacher in succession of Gautama, 683 years after the ''[[Moksha (Jainism)|nirvana]]'' of Mahavira.{{sfn|Dundas|2002|p=79}}\n\nIn the Digambara tradition, the following lineage of teachers are revered: [[Mahavira]], [[Indrabhuti Gautama|Gautama]], [[Kundakunda]],<ref>Jaini, Padmanabh (1991), Gender and Salvation: Jaina Debates on the Spiritual Liberation of Women, University of California Press, pages 31\u201332</ref> [[Bhadrabahu]], [[Umaswati|Umaswami]], [[Samantabhadra (Jain monk)|Samantabhadra]], [[Siddhasena Divakara]],[[Pujyapada]], [[Manatunga]], [[Virasena]],<ref>Satkhandagama : Dhaval (Jivasthana) Satparupana-I (Enunciation of Existence-I) An English Translation of Part 1 of the Dhavala Commentary on the Satkhandagama of Acarya Pushpadanta & Bhutabali Dhavala commentary by Acarya Virasena English tr. by Prof. Nandlal Jain, Ed. by Prof. Ashok Jain {{ISBN|978-81-86957-47-9}}</ref> [[Jinasena]], [[Nemichandra]].{{cn|date=November 2019}}\n\nKundakunda is considered the most significant scholar monk of the Digambara tradition of Jainism. He authored [[Prakrit]] texts such as the ''[[Samayas\u0101ra]]'' and the ''[[Pravacanas\u0101ra]]''. Other prominent ''[[Acharya]]s'' of this tradition were, [[Virasena]] (author of a commentary on the ''[[Dhavala]]''), [[Samantabhadra (Jain monk)|Samantabhadra]] and [[Siddhasena Divakara]]. The ''[[Satkhandagama]]'' and ''[[Kasayapahuda]]'' have major significance in the ''Digambara'' tradition.\n\n==Scripture and literature==\nThe ''Digambara'' sect of Jainism rejects the texts and canonical literature of the ''[[Svetambara]]'' sect.{{sfn|Dundas|2002|pp=79\u201380}}{{sfn|Upinder Singh|2009|p=444}} They believe that the words of Mahavira neither survive nor could be recorded. The original teachings went through a rapid period of decline, state the Digambaras, and Svetambara claims of preserving the sacred knowledge and ancient ''angas'' is false.{{sfn|Dundas|2002|pp=79\u201380}}\n\nAccording to the ''Digambaras'', their 33rd ''ach\u0101rya'' was [[Dharasena]] who knew one ''anga'', and he taught these to [[Pushpadanta (Jain monk)|Pushpadanta]] and [[Bhutabali]], 683 years after the ''[[Moksha (Jainism)|moksha]]'' of Mahavira.{{sfn|Dundas|2002|p=79}} That ''anga'' was also lost with the death of those two. Dharasena's teachings that have survived are ''[[Shatkhandagama|\u1e62a\u1e6dkha\u1e45\u1e0d\u0101gama]]'' (Scripture of Six Parts) and ''Kasayapahuda'' (Treatise on the Passions), which were written on palm leaves near a cave in Mount Girnar (Gujarat) and a copy of which with a 12th-century commentary came to Tulu Nadu (south Karnataka).{{sfn|Dundas|2002|pp=63\u201365, 79\u201380}} This has survived as the Mudbidri manuscripts, which were used by regional Jains not for reading and study, but as an object of devotional worship for centuries.{{sfn|Dundas|2002|pp=63\u201365, 79\u201380}} In the 19th century, the fragile and decaying manuscript was copied and portions of it leaked to scholars between 1896 and 1922 despite objections of Digambara monks. It is considered to be the oldest known ''Digambara'' text ultimately traceable to the 2nd-century CE.{{sfn|Dundas|2002|pp=63\u201365, 79\u201380}} \n\nThese two oldest known Digambara tradition texts \u2013 ''Satkhandagama'' and ''Kasayapahuda'' \u2013 are predominantly a treatise about the soul and [[Karma]] theory, written in Prakrit language. Philologically, the text belongs to about the 2nd-century, and has nothing that suggests it is of \"immemorial antiquity\".{{sfn|Dundas|2002|pp=63\u201365, 79\u201380}} In details, the text is quite similar in its teachings to those found in ''Prajnapana'' \u2013 the 4th ''upanga'' \u2013 of Svetambaras.{{sfn|Dundas|2002|pp=79\u201380}} Between the two, the poetic meter of ''Satkhandagama'' suggests it was composed after the Svetambara text.{{sfn|Dundas|2002|pp=79\u201380}}\n\nDigambaras, unlike Svetambaras, do not have a canon. They do have a quasi-canonical literature grouped into four literary categories called ''anuyoga'' (exposition) since the time of the Digambara scholar Rakshita.{{sfn|Dundas|2002|p=80}} The ''prathmanuyoga'' (first exposition) contains the universal history, the ''karananuyoga'' (calculation exposition) contains works on cosmology, the ''charananuyoga'' (behaviour exposition) includes texts about proper behaviour for monks and lay people, while the ''dravyanuyoga'' (entity exposition) contains metaphysical discussions.{{sfn|Dundas|2002|p=80}} In the Digambara tradition, it is not the oldest texts that have survived in its temples and monasteries that attract the most study or reverence, rather it is the late 9th-century ''Mahapurana'' (universal history) of Jinasena that is the most revered and cherished.{{sfn|Dundas|2002|pp=80-81}} The ''Mahapurana'' includes not only religious history, but also the mythical sociological history of the Jaina people \u2013 including the Jain caste system and its origins as formulated by [[Rishabhanatha]] \u2013 from the Digambara Jaina perspective.{{sfn|Jaini|2000|pp=32, 229\u2013239}}\n\nThe ''Digamabara'' tradition maintains a long list of revered teachers, and this list includes Kundakunda, Samantabhadra, Pujyapada, Jinasena, Akalanka, Vidyanandi, Somadeva and Asadhara.{{sfn|Jaini|2000|p=28}}\n\n==Practices==\n===Monasticism===\n{{Main|Digambara monk}}\nThe lifestyle and behavioral conduct of a ''Digambara'' monk is guided by a code called ''mulacara'' (''mulachara''). This includes 28 ''m\u016bla gu\u0146as'' (primary attributes) for the monk.{{sfn|Pramansagar|2008|p=189\u2013191}} The oldest text containing these norms is the 2nd-century ''[[Mulachara]]'' attributed to Vattekara, that probably originated in the Mathura region.{{sfn|Dundas|2002|p=80}} \n\nThese are: 5 ''mah\u0101vratas'' (great vows); 5 ''samitis'' (restraints); 5 ''indriya nirodha'' (control of the five senses); 6 ''\u0101va\u015byakas'' (essential observations); and 7 ''niyamas'' (rules).{{sfn|Vijay K. Jain|2013|pp=189\u2013191, 196\u2013197}}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! No.\n! ''Guna''<br>(attribute)\n! Remarks\n|- style=\"background:#ffedcd;\"\n|rowspan=\"5\"|''Mahavratas''-<br /> Five Great Vows{{sfn|Vijay K. Jain|2011|p=93\u2013100}}{{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1926|p=26}}\n|1. ''[[Ahimsa in Jainism|Ahimsa]]''\n|neither injure, nor ask, nor encourage another to injure any living being through actions, words or thoughts. This includes injury caused by cooking, starting a fire to cook, plucking a fruit, or any conduct that harms living beings{{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1926|pp=27\u201328}}\n|- style=\"background:#ffedcd;\"\n|2. [[Satya]]\n| To speak the truth, to remain silent if his speaking the truth will lead to injury to living beings{{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1926|p=29}}\n|- style=\"background:#ffedcd;\" \n|3. ''[[Asteya]]''\n| Not to take anything unless given, and not accepting anything more than what is necessary and needed{{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1926|p=30}}\n|- style=\"background:#ffedcd;\"\n|4. ''[[Brahmacharya]]''\n|No sex, no natural or unnatural sexual gratification through action (viewing, participating, encouraging), words (hearing, reciting, reading, writing), or thoughts{{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1926|pp=30\u201331}}\n|- style=\"background:#ffedcd;\"\n|5. ''[[Aparigraha]]''\n|Renunciation of all worldly things, property, want, and all possessions external to soul{{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1926|pp=31\u201332}}\n|- style=\"background:#ffe4b3;\"\n|rowspan=\"5\"|''Samiti''-<br /> Regulations{{sfn|Vijay K. Jain|2012|p=144\u2013145}}{{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1926|pp=32\u201338}}\n|6. ''irya''\n|Walk carefully on much trodden paths, after viewing land to the extent of four cubits (2 yards). Do not walk in the dark or on the grass to avoid accidental injury to other living beings.{{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1926|p=33}} He should not run to save himself if charged by a wild animal or if a violent person is about to injure him, as running can cause injury to other living beings.{{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1926|p=33}}\n|- style=\"background:#ffe4b3;\"\n|7. ''bhasha''\n| Avoid slander, back-biting, false speech. He must avoid intentionally long or short statements that mislead or help create misunderstanding, doubts, misinformation, hypocrisy, bad blood or conceit in his audience.{{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1926|pp=34\u201335}}\n|- style=\"background:#ffe4b3;\"\n|8. ''esana''\n|To never accept objectionable food nor eat more palatable items from those received.{{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1926|pp=35\u201336}}\n|- style=\"background:#ffe4b3;\"\n|9. ''adana-nikshepana''\n|Carefulness in the handling the ''pichchi'' (feather bundle to remove insects in his path) and ''kamandalu'' (hollow vegetable gourd to filter water)\n|- style=\"background:#ffe4b3;\"\n|10. ''pratish\u1e6dapan''\n|To excrete body waste after carefully brushing aside insects and other living beings.{{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1926|pp=37\u201338}}\n|- style=\"background:#faba00;\" \n|rowspan=\"1\"|''Indrinirodh''{{sfn|Vijay K. Jain|2013|pp=189\u2013191, 196\u2013197}}\n|11\u201315. Control of the five senses\n|Shedding all attachment and aversion towards the sense objects pertaining to touch (''spar\u015bana''), taste (''rasana''), smell (''ghr\u0101\u1e47a''), sight (''cak\u015bu''), and hearing (''\u015brotra''). The ''sadhu'' (monk) must eradicate all desires and activities that please the mind through his senses.{{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1926|pp=38\u201339}} He must end all ties, relationships and entanglements with his family and friends before he renounced.{{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1926|pp=38\u201339}}\n|- style=\"background:#ffd280;\"\n|rowspan=\"6\"|''Avasyakas'' \u2013<br>Essential observations{{sfn|Vijay K. Jain|2012|p=143}}{{sfn|Vijay K. Jain|2013|pp=189\u2013191, 196\u2013197}}\n|16. ''[[S\u0101m\u0101yika]]''\n|Practice equanimous dispassion towards everything for eighteen ''ghari'' a day (1 ''ghari'' = about 24 minutes){{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1926|pp=38\u201339}} This \n|- style=\"background:#ffd280;\" \n|17. ''stuti''\n|Salute the divine (''[[Tirthankaras]]'')\n|- style=\"background:#ffd280;\" \n|18. ''vandana''\n|Medidate upon and adore ''acharyas'', ''gurus'', idols and images of gods{{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1926|pp=26, 38\u201339}}<ref name=\"CaillatBalbir2008p236\">{{cite book|author1= Colette Caillat|author2= Nalini Balbir|title=Jaina Studies |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=ecKCrO6nLiAC |year=2008|publisher= Motilal Banarsidass |isbn=978-81-208-3247-3|pages=236\u2013241 with footnotes }}</ref><ref name=\"Wiley2009p226\">{{cite book|author=Kristi L. Wiley|title=The A to Z of Jainism |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=cIhCCwAAQBAJ |year=2009 |publisher=Scarecrow |isbn= 978-0-8108-6337-8|pages=226\u2013227}}</ref>\n|- style=\"background:#ffd280;\"\n|19. ''[[Pratikramana]]''\n| Confession, repentance and self-censure for having violated any vows and rules of conduct;<ref name=\"Wiley2009p170\">{{cite book|author=Kristi L. Wiley|title=The A to Z of Jainism |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cIhCCwAAQBAJ |year=2009|publisher=Scarecrow |isbn=978-0-8108-6337-8|page=170}}</ref> dissociate one's soul from any virtuous or evil ''karmas'', in the current or past lives.\n|- style=\"background:#ffd280;\" \n|20. ''Pratikhayan''\n|Recite mantra that lists and promises future renunciation of food, drink and comforts and to forfend future faults<ref name=\"Williams1991p184\">{{cite book|author=Robert Williams|title=Jaina Yoga: A Survey of the Mediaeval \u015ar\u0101vak\u0101c\u0101ras |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=LLKcrIJ6oscC&pg=PA184 |year=1991|publisher= Motilal Banarsidass|isbn =978-81-208-0775-4 |pages=184 }}</ref>\n|- style=\"background:#ffd280;\" \n|21. ''[[Kayotsarga]]''\n|Giving up attachment to the body for a limited period of time.<ref name=\"Williams1991p184\"/> Typically, this is a standing naked and motionless posture of a form common in [[Bahubali]] iconography.<ref>{{cite book|author=Umakant Premanand Shah|title=Jaina-r\u016bpa-ma\u1e47\u1e0dana|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=m_y_P4duSXsC&pg=PA79 |year=1987|publisher=Abhinav Publications|isbn=978-81-7017-208-6|pages=79\u201380 }}</ref>\n|- style=\"background:#ffdb9a;\" \n|rowspan=\"7\"|''Niyama''-<br /> Rules{{sfn|Vijay K. Jain|2013|pp=189\u2013191, 196\u2013197}}{{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1926|p=46\u201347}}\n|22. ''adantdhavan''\n|Never clean teeth{{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1926|p=47\u201348}}\n|- style=\"background:#ffdb9a;\"\n|23. ''bhushayan''\n|Sleep on hard ground\n|- style=\"background:#ffdb9a;\"\n|24. ''asn\u0101na''\n|Never bathe{{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1926|p=46\u201347}}\n|- style=\"background:#ffdb9a;\"\n|25. ''stithi-bhojan''\n|Eat food in standing posture, accept food in open palms (no utensils){{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1926|p=47\u201348}}\n|- style=\"background:#ffdb9a;\"\n|26. ''{{lang|sa-Latn|ahara}}''\n|Eat food once a day,{{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1926|p=48\u201349}} drink water only when eating meal{{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1926|p=36}}\n|- style=\"background:#ffdb9a;\"\n|27. ''ke\u015ba-lonch''\n|To periodically pluck all hair on his body by his own hand.{{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1926|p=44\u201345}}\n|- style=\"background:#ffdb9a;\"\n|28. nudity\n|Remain completely nude all the time (''digambara''){{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1926|p=45\u201346}}\n|- style=\"background:#ffdb9a;\"\n|}\n\n''Digambara'' monks do not wear any clothes as it is considered to be ''parigraha'' (possession), which ultimately leads to attachment.{{sfn|Dundas|2002|p=45}} The monks carry ''picchi'', a broom made up of fallen peacock feathers for removing small insects to avoid causing injury and ''Kamandalu'' (the gourd for carrying pure, sterilized water).{{sfn|Upinder Singh|2009|p=316}}{{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1926|p=36}} The head of all monastics is called ''[[Acharya|\u0100ch\u0101rya]]'', while the saintly preceptor of saints is the ''up\u0101dhy\u0101ya''.{{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1926|p=21}} The ''\u0100ch\u0101rya'' has 36 primary attributes (''m\u016bla gu\u0146a'') in addition to the 28 mentioned above.{{sfn|Vijay K. Jain|2013|pp=189\u2013191, 196\u2013197}} \n\nThe monks perform ''kayotsarga'' daily, in a rigid and immobile posture, with the arms held stiffly down, knees straight, and toes directed forward.{{sfn|Zimmer|1953|p=210}}\n\n===Nuns===\nFemale monastics in Digambara tradition are known as ''[[aryika]]s''.{{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1926|p=141}} Digambara nuns, unlike the monks in their tradition, wear clothes. Given their beliefs such as non-attachment and non-possession, the Digambara tradition has held that women cannot achieve salvation (moksha) as men can, and the best a nun can achieve is to be reborn as a man in the next rebirth.<ref name=\"Long2013p17\"/> The monks are held to be of higher status than nuns in Digambara monasteries, states Jeffery Long.<ref name=\"Long2013p17\"/> From the Digambara monk's perspective, both Digambara nuns and Svetambara monastic community are simply more pious Jain layperson, who do not or are unable to fully practice the Jain monastic vows.{{sfn|Dundas|2002|pp=49-50}}\n\nDigambara nuns are relatively rare in comparison to the nuns found in Svetambara traditions. According to a 1970s and 1980s survey of Jain subtraditions, there were about 125 Digambara monks in India and 50 Digambara nuns.<ref name=\"Howard2019pt105\">{{cite book|author=Veena R. Howard |title=The Bloomsbury Research Handbook of Indian Philosophy and Gender|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=J1OqDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT105 |year=2019|publisher=Bloomsbury Academic |isbn=978-1-4742-6959-9 |pages=105\u2013106}}</ref> This compared to 3,400 nuns and 1,200 monks in the Svetambara tradition.<ref name=\"Howard2019pt105\"/>\n\n===Digambar akhara===\n{{anchor | Digambar akhara}}\n\nThe '''Digambar Akhara''', which along with other [[akhara]]s, also participates in various inter-sectarian (''[[sampradaya]]'') religious activities  including [[Kumbh Mela]]s, is completely unrelated to Digambar Jain tradition, even though they also practice nudity.<ref name=relDis1>[South Asian Religions on Display: Religious Processions in South Asia and in the Diaspora, Knut A. Jacobsen, ISBN hardback 978-0-415-4373-3, ISBN ebook ISBN hardback 978-0-203-93059-5]</ref>\n\n===Worship===\n[[File:7th - 12th century Mahavira flanked by 24 Tirthankaras in Cave 4, Badami Jain cave temple Karnataka.jpg|thumb|Adinatha image (Badami caves)]]\nThe ''Digambara'' Jains worship completely nude idols of ''tirthankaras'' (omniscient beings) and ''[[siddha]]'' (liberated souls). The ''tirthankara'' is represented either seated in yoga posture or standing in the ''Kayotsarga'' posture.{{sfn|Zimmer|1953|p=209\u2013210}} \n{{quote|The truly \"sky-clad\" (''digambara'') Jaina statue expresses the perfect isolation of the one who has stripped off every bond. His is an absolute \"abiding in itself,\" a strange but perfect aloofness, a nudity of chilling majesty, in its stony simplicity, rigid contours, and abstraction.{{sfn|Zimmer|1953|p=213}}|[[Heinrich Zimmer]]}}\n\n==== Statues ====\n<gallery>\nKizhavalavu (Kilavalavu) -Jain Sculptures.JPG|Kizhavalavu ([[Keelavalavu]]) Sculptures\nGommateshvara Bahubali.jpg|The {{convert|57|ft|m}} high [[Gommateshwara statue]], [[Shravanabelagola]]\nJain statues, Gwalior.jpg|''Tirthankara'' statues at [[Siddhachal Caves]] inside [[Gwalior Fort]], [[Madhya Pradesh]]\nJain statue of Parshvanath, Naugaza temple, Alwar district, Rajasthan, India.jpg|''Tirthankara'' [[Parshvanatha]] statue, [[Rajasthan]]\n</gallery>\n\n==Monastic lineages==\nThere have been several Digambara monastic lineages that all trace their descent to Lord Mahavira. The historical linages included ''[[Mula Sangha]]'' (further vivided into  ''Nandi'', ''Sena'', ''Simha'' and ''Deva'' Sanghas) and now largely extinct [[Kashtha Sangha]] (which included ''Mathura'' sangha, \"\"Lat-Vagad\" etc.), Dravida Sangh.   {{sfn|Carrithers|Humphrey|1991|p=170}} The text Darshana-Sara of Devasena <ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=dXVOXRrYQiQC&pg=PA433&lpg=PA433&dq=darshan+sar+jain+book&source=bl&ots=-lHX9hgrTj&sig=ACfU3U03FFsSGhE4iygTZmTOkrxi1RoxNg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj-qLv67qHkAhVWvZ4KHbkvBcEQ6AEwEHoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=darshan%20sar%20jain%20book&f=false Agama Aura Tripitaka: Eka Anusilana, Volume 2 of \u0100gama Aura Tripi\u1e6daka, Eka Anu\u015bilana, Nagraj (Muni.), Concept Publishing Company, 1986, p. 433]</ref> discusses the supposed differences among the orders. The ''Mula sangha'' orders include ''Deshiya Gana'' (Bhattarakas of Shravanabelgola etc.) and ''[[Balatkara Gana]]'' (Bhattarakas of [[Humcha]], and numerous linages of North/Central India) traditions.<ref>Vidaydgar Johrapurkar, Bha\u1e6d\u1e6d\u0101raka Sampradaya, Solapur, 1958</ref> The ''[[Bhattaraka]]s'' of [[Shravanabelagola]] and [[Mudbidri]] belong to ''Deshiya Gana'' and the ''Bhattaraka'' of [[Humbaj]] belongs to the ''Balatkara Gana''.{{sfn|Sangave|1980|p=299}}\n\nThe extinct [[Yapaniya]] order used nudity like the Digambara orders, but followed some Shvetambara tenets.\n\n==Sub-sects==\n[[File:Acharya5.jpg|thumb|''[[Acharya]]'' [[Vidyasagar (Jain monk)|Vidyasagar]], a prominent [[Digambara monk]]]]\n{{Jain Digambara sects}}\n\nModern ''Digambara'' community is divided into various sub-sects viz. ''[[Digambara Terapanth|Terapanthi]]'', ''[[Bispanthi]]'', ''[[Taran Panth|Taranpanthi]]'' (or ''Samayiapanthi''), ''Gumanapanthi'' and ''Totapanthi''.{{sfn|Sangave|1980|pp=51-56}}\n\nDigambara community was divided into ''Terapanthi'' and ''Bisapanthi'' on the acceptance of authority of ''Bhattaraka''.{{sfn|Long|2008|p=39}}{{Citation not found}}\n\nThe  Bispanth-Terapanth division among the Digambaras emerged in the 17th century in the Jaipur region: [[Sanganer]], [[Amer, India|Amer]] and [[Jaipur]] itself.<ref>John E. Cort \"A Tale of Two Cities: On the Origins of Digambara Sectarianism in North India.\" L. A. Babb, V. Joshi, and M. W. Meister (eds.), Multiple Histories: Culture and Society in the Study of Rajasthan, 39-83. Jaipur: Rawat, 2002.</ref>\n\n===''Terapanthi''===\n{{Main|Digambara Terapanth}}\n[[File:Acharya Gyansagar.jpg|thumb|Acharya [[Gyansagar (Chani)|Gyansagar]]]]\nThe ''Terapanthis'' worship what the idols represent, with ''ashta-dravya'' similarly to the Bispanthis, but replace flowers and fruits with dry substitutes.  The ashta-dravya ''jal'' (water), ''chandan'' (sandal), ''akshata'' (sacred rice), ''pushp'' (yellow rice), ''deep'' (yellow dry coconut), ''dhup'' (''kapoor'' or cloves) and ''phal'' (almonds).{{sfn|Sangave|1980|p=52}} Terapanthi is a reformist sect of ''Digambara'' Jainism that distinguished itself from the ''[[Bispanthi]]'' sect. It formed out of strong opposition to the religious domination of traditional religious leaders called ''[[bhattaraka]]s'' in the 17th century.  They oppose the worship of various minor gods and goddesses. Some ''Terapanthi'' practices, like not using flowers in worship, are followed by most of [[North India]]n Jains. ''Terapanthis'' occur in large numbers in [[Rajasthan]], [[Uttar Pradesh]] and [[Madhya Pradesh]].{{sfn|Sangave|1980|p=52}}\n\nThe Terapanthi movement was born out of the ''Adhyatma'' movement that arose in 1626 AD ([[Vikram Samvat|V.S.]] 1683) in [[Agra]]. Its leading proponent was [[Banarasidas]] of Agra.<ref>Ardhakathanaka: Half a tale, a Study in the Interrelationship between Autobiography and History, Mukunda Lath (trans. and ed.), Jaipur 2005. {{ISBN|978-8129105660}}</ref>{{better source|date=March 2018}}\n\n===''Bispanthi''===\n{{Main|Bispanthi}}\nBesides ''tirthankaras'', ''Bispanthi'' also worship ''[[Yaksha]]'' and ''[[Yakshini]]'' like [[Bhairava]] and [[Kshetrapala]]. Their religious practices include ''[[aarti]]'' and offerings of flowers, fruits and ''[[prasad]]''. ''Bhattarakas'' are their ''dharma-gurus'' and they are concentrated in Rajasthan, [[Gujarat]], Maharastra and South India. {{sfn|Sangave|1980|p=52}}\n\n== Differences with \u015av\u0113t\u0101mbara sect ==\nAccording to ''Digambara'' texts, after attaining ''[[Kevala Jnana]]'' (omniscience), ''[[Arihant (Jainism)|arihant]]'' (omniscient beings) are free from human needs like hunger, thirst, and sleep.{{sfn|Upinder Singh|2009|p=314}} In contrast, \u015av\u0113t\u0101mbara texts preach that it is not so. According to the ''Digambara'' tradition, a soul can attain ''moksha'' (liberation) only from the male body with complete nudity being a necessity.{{sfn|Upinder Singh|2009|p=319}} While, \u015av\u0113t\u0101mbaras believe that women can attain liberation from female body itself and renunciation of clothes is not at all necessary.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Religion}}\n*[[Nudity in religion]]\n*[[God in Jainism]]\n*[[Kshullak]]\n*[[Jain philosophy]]\n*[[Timeline of Jainism]]\n*[[Digambar Jain Mahasabha]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|20em}}\n\n===Sources===\n* {{citation |editor-last=Carrithers |editor-first=Michael |editor-link=Michael Carrithers |editor-last2=Humphrey |editor-first2=Caroline |editor-link2=Caroline Humphrey |title=The Assembly of Listeners: Jains in Society |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LW8czr_HzzwC |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |date=1991 |isbn=0-521-365-05-8 }}\n* {{citation |title=\u0100c\u0101rya Nemichandra's Dravyasa\u1e43graha |isbn=978-81-903639-5-2 |last=Jain |first=Vijay K. |date=2013 |quote={{PD-notice}} |publisher=Vikalp Printers |ref={{sfnref|Vijay K. Jain|2013}} }}\n* {{citation |last=Jain |first=Vijay K. |title=Acharya Amritchandra's Purushartha Siddhyupaya |year=2012 |publisher=Vikalp Printers |isbn=978-81-903639-4-5 |url=https://books.google.com/books?isbn=8190363948 |quote={{PD-notice}} |ref={{sfnref|Vijay K. Jain|2012}} }}\n*{{citation |last=Jain |first=Vijay K. |title=Acharya Umasvami's Tattv\u0101rths\u016btra |publisher=Vikalp Printers |location=(Uttarakhand) India |isbn=978-81-903639-2-1 |edition=1st |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zLmx9bvtglkC |year=2011 |quote={{PD-notice}} |ref={{sfnref|Vijay K. Jain|